# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: escalator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] The **Rehabilitation Act of 1973** (Pub.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] 355, enacted September 26, 1973) is a United States federal law, codified at 29 U.S.C. § 701 et seq.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] The principal sponsor of the bill was Rep.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] It created the Rehabilitation Services Administration.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] The standards for determining employment discrimination under the Rehabilitation Act are the same as those used in title I of the Americans with Disabilities Act.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] 8070 into law on September 26, 1973 after he had vetoed two previous versions.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] An accessible information technology system is one that can be operated in a variety of ways and does not rely on a single sense or ability of the user.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] For example, a system that provides output only in visual format may not be accessible to people with visual impairments, and a system that provides output only in audio format may not be accessible to people who are deaf or hard of hearing.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Some individuals with disabilities may need accessibility-related software or peripheral devices in order to use systems that comply with Section 508.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Experts in civil rights laws are involved in education of governments, Americans with disabilities, citizens, special interest groups (e.g., disability classes), non-profit and for-profit agencies, and community groups on the "application of these federal laws" in daily lives, including workplaces.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] In the area of employment law, Syracuse University's Peter Blanck, Executive of the Burton Blatt Institute since it was founded in 2005, has offered detailed advice on the implementation of central concepts of the employment-rehabilitation laws.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] While the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) of 1990 is the current base law, the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, amended in 1978 is also cited in these legal cases, including accommodations for individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Hearings at the local levels often do not recognize experts in practice, and thus legal cases repeatedly must be appealed through the federal systems.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Personal assistance in the workplace has also been supported as a reasonable accommodation, a central concept in employment and disability law (Sections IV &4.8, 4.11; XI & 11.6, 11.8, 11.10; XVI & 16.7, 16.8).
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] The American Association on Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities has indicated that supported employment is considered to be a workplace accommodation under the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990 (Sections IV & 4.7, 4.11; XI & 11.6, 11.8, 11.10: XVI & 16.7,16.8).
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Significant amendments were made to the Rehabilitation Act in 1974.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] In 1986, Public Law 99-506 helped the Rehabilitation Act to refine and focus services offered to those with the most severe disabilities.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Supported employment was also defined as a "legitimate rehabilitation outcome".
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Title four of the Workforce Investment Act of 1998 amended the Rehabilitation Act in order to work with the WIA to accomplish the goal of helping people return to the workforce.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] Title four created a national council on disability, appointed by the president, to link rehabilitation programs to state and local workforce development systems.
[src:escalator/1973-rehabilitation-act] However, the Workforce Investment Act was repealed and replaced by the 2014 Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act.
[src:escalator/acton-london] At the 2011 census, its four wards, East Acton, Acton Central, South Acton and Southfield, had a population of 62,480, a ten-year increase of 8,791 people.
[src:escalator/acton-london] North Acton, West Acton, East Acton, South Acton, Acton Green, Acton Town, Acton Vale and Acton Central are all parts of Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton means "oak farm" or "farm by oak trees", and is derived from the Old English *āc* (oak) and *tūn* (farm).
[src:escalator/acton-london] Originally an ancient village, as London expanded, Acton was absorbed into the city.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Since 1965, Acton equates to the east of the London Borough of Ealing, though some of East Acton is in the London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham and a small portion of South Acton is in the London Borough of Hounslow.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Central Acton is synonymous with the hub of commerce and retail on the former main road between London and Oxford (the Uxbridge Road); a reminder of its history is in its inns, which in some cases date back to the late Tudor period as stopping places for travellers.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Nowadays, the principal route linking London and Oxford (the A40 dual carriageway) bypasses central Acton, but passes through East Acton and North Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton's name derives from the Old English words *āc* (oak) and *tūn* (enclosed garden, enclosure), meaning "a garden or a field enclosed by oaks".
[src:escalator/acton-london] Later, in the Middle Ages *tūn* became a synonym for "farm" or "farm by oak trees".
[src:escalator/acton-london] For several centuries, its name bore the prefix *Church* (hence *Chirche Acton*, *Churche Acton*, etc.) to distinguish it from the separate hamlet of East Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] A number of finds indicate prehistoric settlement in Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The earliest are a cluster of Upper Palaeolithic and Mesolithic flint cores, flakes and artefacts found mainly to the north of Churchfield Road.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Around the Mill Hill Park area, a Neolithic axe, and a group of Bronze Age Deverel-Rimbury urns and cremated bone were found, along with an Iron Age pot shard.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Iron Age coins were also found near Bollo Lane.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Roman period is represented by a ditch in the same area, and a hoard north of Springfield Gardens.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In the Middle Ages the northern half of the parish was heavily wooded.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Oaks and elms still stood along roads and hedgerows and in private grounds in the early 20th century, but most of the woodland had been cleared by the 17th century, even on the extensive Old Oak common.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Landholders figuring in county records were resident by 1222 and houses were recorded from the late 13th century.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The main settlement, Church Acton or Acton town, lay slightly west of the centre of the parish along the highway to Oxford (Uxbridge Road) at the 5-mile post out of London.
[src:escalator/acton-london] By 1380 some of the tenements, such as *The Tabard* and *The Cock*, along the south side of the road, were inns.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The hamlet of East Acton, mentioned in 1294, consisted of farmhouses and cottages north and south of common land known as East Acton green by 1474.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Medieval settlement was mainly around the two hamlets.
[src:escalator/acton-london] At Church Acton most of the farmhouses lay along the Oxford road or Horn Lane, with only a few outlying farms.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Friars Place Farm at the north end of Horn Lane and the moated site to the west, occupied until the 15th century, were early farms.
[src:escalator/acton-london] East of Friars Place farm were commons: Worton or Watton Green and Rush green in the 16th and 17th centuries, and Friars Place in the 18th century, where there was some settlement by 1664.
[src:escalator/acton-london] To the north-west were Acton or Old Oak wells, known by 1613.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In the parish's extreme south, a few farmhouses on the northern side of Acton common or Acton Green were mentioned as in Turnham Green until the 19th century and were linked more closely with that village than with Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] *Gregories*, mentioned in 1551 as a copyhold tenement with 30 a. near Bollo Lane and the Brentford high road, probably lay in Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Londoners were increasingly involved in land sales from the early 14th century but apparently did not live in Acton until the late 15th.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The manor, part of Fulham, had no resident (demesne) lord, and apart from a brief period before c.
[src:escalator/acton-london] 1735, when a branch of the landed Somerset (Duke of Beaufort's) family lived in Acton, there were no large resident landowners.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Many of the tenements without land, including most of the inns, frequently changed hands.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The parish had 158 communicants in 1548.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In 1664 it had 72 chargeable households and 59 exempt, with 6 empty houses.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Six houses had 10 or more hearths, 16 had from 5 to 9, 33 had 3 or 4, 23 had 2, and 53 had 1.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton had about 160 families resident in the mid 18th century.
[src:escalator/acton-london] By the 17th century Acton's proximity to London had made it a summer retreat for courtiers and lawyers.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Sir Richard Sutton bought the seat at East Acton known later as Manor House in 1610 and Sir Henry Garraway probably rebuilt Acton House in 1638.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton was lauded as "blessed with very sweet air" in 1706 by rector urging a friend in verse to move there.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The fashion for medicinal waters brought a brief period of fame, with the exploitation of the wells at Old Oak common, when East Acton and Friars Place were said to be thronged with summer visitors, who had brought about improvement in the houses there.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Although high society had left Acton by the mid 18th century, many professional and military men bought houses there, sometimes including a small park, until well into the 19th century.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The break-up of the 800 acres (3.2 km2) Fetherstonhaugh estate, which had had no resident owner, produced four or five small estates whose owners, professional men such as Samuel Wegg, John Winter, and Richard White, were active in parish affairs.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Grand early homes included: Heathfield Lodge, West Lodge, and East Lodge by Winter c.
[src:escalator/acton-london] 1800, Mill Hill House by White, and Woodlands at Acton Hill soon afterwards.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton Green also became increasingly popular, being near Chiswick High Road (the Great West Road).
[src:escalator/acton-london] Fairlawn, substantial, on west side of the green, was the home of the botanist John Lindley (1797–1865) as was the house to the north and Bedford House, another home of Lindley, and Melbourne House further east.
[src:escalator/acton-london] A short row of houses had been built on the south side of the green by 1800.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In 1804, Derwentwater House was built in the grounds of Acton House by the Selby family.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In 1812, twenty almshouses were built by the Worshipful Company of Goldsmiths on the former Perryn estate, on land which had been left to the company by John Perryn in 1657.
[src:escalator/acton-london] There were 241 inhabited houses in 1801 and 426 by 1831.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Growth took place mainly in the established residential neighbourhoods of Acton town and East Acton, but Acton Green also had acquired a cluster of cottages and houses at the bottom of Acton Lane by 1842.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The few mansions contrasted sharply with most of the houses, which were described as 'beneath mediocrity of character'.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Despite an overall rise in the number of houses, poor rates had to be increased in the 1820s because of a growing number of empty dwellings.
[src:escalator/acton-london] More widespread building was planned and took place in the 1850s.
[src:escalator/acton-london] As a result of its soft water sources, Acton became famous for its laundries and at the end of the 19th century there were around 170 establishments in South Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] These laundries would serve hotels and the rich in London's West End, leading to the nickname "Soapsuds Island" or "Soap Sud City".
[src:escalator/acton-london] At least 600 different laundries operated within South Acton, the last laundry closed in the late 1970s and is now a low redbrick block of flats.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The parish of Acton formed a local board of health in 1865 and became an urban district in 1894.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In 1895, Acton Cemetery was opened on farmland near to what is now North Acton Station.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The town was incorporated as the Municipal Borough of Acton in 1921.
[src:escalator/acton-london] This authority combined with the municipal boroughs of Ealing and Southall to form the London Borough of Ealing, within Greater London, in 1965.
[src:escalator/acton-london] An Acton Golf Club was founded in 1896, which closed in 1920 and the area was redeveloped for housing.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton formed an urban district and, later, municipal borough of Middlesex from 1894 to 1965.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Its former area was used to form part of the London Borough of Ealing in 1965.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The industries of North Acton merged with the great industrial concentrations of Park Royal and Harlesden.
[src:escalator/acton-london] During the 20th century Acton was a major industrial centre employing tens of thousands of people, particularly in the motor vehicles and components industries.
[src:escalator/acton-london] These included car manufacturer Renault, that built the 4CV and Dauphine, at a factory in North Acton from 1926 until 1960.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Renault has remained on the site continuously since the 1920s and still has its main London showroom on the Park Royal site.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Alfred Mond built a nickel carbonyl refinery here that was able to produce platinum as a by-product of the matte from Inco's Sudbury Basin operations.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Further south Acton Vale had manufacturers including Napier & Son (engines), H.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Bronnley & Co (Soaps), Evershed & Vignoles (electrical equipment), Lucas CAV (automotive electrical), Vandervell Products (bearings), and Wilkinson Sword (swords and razors).
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton is now principally residential, with some light industry, particularly in the northeast Park Royal area, and the south near the border with Chiswick.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Waitrose was founded on Acton High Street near the police station, as Waite, Rose and Taylor, with its second shop opening in Churchfield Road in 1913.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton has the largest housing estate in west London, the South Acton estate, with approximately 2,000 homes and 5,800 residents.
[src:escalator/acton-london] This area is currently in the Phase 2 of a major 15-year phased regeneration which includes near-total demolition of the existing residential units, and the construction of new and more numerous residential units.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Since World War II, Acton has had a small but notable population of Polish immigrants.
[src:escalator/acton-london] In recent years, a number of Antipodean immigrants have settled there; there are several Australian and South African pubs concentrated in a small area.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Japanese School in London has also attracted a Japanese community to West Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] East Acton's King Fahd Academy also attracted Arab and mainly Saudi immigrants to the area.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Somali community is concentrated around Church Road, and there are two mosques near the High Street.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Irish community has diminished somewhat in recent years, but there are still a number of Irish pubs in the area.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton has the starting point of the 25 kilometre Thames Tideway Tunnel (also known as the "Super Sewer") at the Acton Storm Tanks in Canham Road.
[src:escalator/acton-london] This will be built to avoid the discharge of sewage from Combined Sewer Overflow into the River Thames.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Mount on Acton High Street hosts a market on Thursday, Friday and Saturday.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Visitors can shop at stalls selling a range of produce.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton's library, swimming baths (built in 1904) and Town Hall are examples of tall Victorian municipal buildings that can be found along the High Street.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Swimming Baths closed in December 2011 for a three-year development project, replacing the existing pools with a 25m 8-lane pool and a smaller teaching pool.
[src:escalator/acton-london] An indoor climbing wall opened on the high street, housed in a building constructed in the 1920s as an Art Deco cinema.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The building was later used as a bingo hall before being refurbished into a bouldering centre.
[src:escalator/acton-london] On the east end of Acton High Street is Acton Park, which features mini golf, bar and pizza restaurant operated by Putt in the Park.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The southeastern bcorner of the park includes tennis courts, outdoor fitness equipment and a multi-purpose basketball and 5-a-side football court.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The park also features a large children's play area including, an adventure playground partially created from local trees felled during a storm, a pond, an art block and a skate park, run by the Ealing Skatepark Association, which opened in April 2019.
[src:escalator/acton-london] There are six state-funded primary schools in Acton, Berrymede Junior School, Derwentwater Primary School, East Acton Primary School, St Vincent's RC Primary School, West Acton Primary School, West Twyford Primary School.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Ark (charity) has opened two primary academies in Acton, Ark Priory Primary Academy in 2013 and Ark Byron Primary Academy in 2015, the latter is based in Acton Park.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton has three state-funded secondary high schools, Ark Acton Academy (formerly Acton High School), Twyford Church of England High School and The Ellen Wilkinson School for Girls.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton was once home to another independent school, Haberdashers' Aske's School for Girls before it changed its site to Elstree, the Acton site becoming the Cardinal Newman Roman Catholic High School.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The Japanese School in London is in Acton.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton has seven railway stations bearing its name, more than any other place in the United Kingdom other than London itself.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton is also the only place in London to have stations named after all four of its cardinal points, north, south, east, and west.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The widespread provision of train services reflects a long railway history, particularly associated (historically) with London Transport and the Great Western Railway.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Between 1858 and 1864 there was a further station on the North London Railway, *Acton Junction*, where the line to Hammersmith & Chiswick railway station branched off.
[src:escalator/acton-london] North Acton has a large Great Western Railway housing estate (now privately owned), and the Old Oak Common TMD railway depot is within the usual boundary, as is the London Transport Museum Depot which houses an extensive collection of historic and heritage rolling stock.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton Main Line station has a busy freight yard (operating ballast and container trains).
[src:escalator/acton-london] Transport for London, led by then Mayor of London, Ken Livingstone, proposed to build a West London Tram between Shepherd's Bush and Uxbridge town centre.
[src:escalator/acton-london] It would have run along the A4020, the Uxbridge Road, through Acton, Ealing, West Ealing, Hanwell, Southall and Hayes End.
[src:escalator/acton-london] This proposed scheme was highly controversial and resulted in strong differences in opinion between TfL, who supported the scheme, and local councils throughout the proposed route, who all took a 'no tram' stance.
[src:escalator/acton-london] The West London Tram was finally scrapped when former Prime Minister Gordon Brown agreed that the long-awaited Crossrail would go ahead in October 2007.
[src:escalator/acton-london] Acton Main Line railway station is now a station on the Elizabeth line, delivered by the Crossrail project, with 4 trains per hour in each direction.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] An **aerial tramway**, **aerial tram**, **sky tram**, **cable car** or **aerial cablecar**, **aerial cableway** or **ropeway** is a type of aerial lift that uses one or two stationary cables for support, with a third moving cable providing propulsion.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] With this form of lift, the grip of an aerial tramway cabin is fixed onto the propulsion cable and cannot be decoupled from it during operation.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Aerial tramways usually provide lower line capacities and longer wait times than gondola lifts.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It is also sometimes called a *ropeway* or even incorrectly referred to as a gondola lift.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] A gondola lift has cabins suspended from a continuously circulating cable whereas aerial trams simply shuttle back and forth on cables.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] In Japan, the two are considered as the same category of vehicle and called *ropeway*, while the term *cable car* refers to both ground-level cable cars and funiculars.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] An aerial railway where the vehicles are suspended from a fixed track as opposed to a cable is known as a suspension railway.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] An aerial tramway consists of one or two fixed cables (called *track cables*), one loop of cable (called a *haulage rope*), and one or two passenger or cargo cabins.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The fixed cables provide support for the cabins while the haulage rope, by means of a grip, is solidly connected to the truck (the wheel set that rolls on the track cables).
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] An electric motor drives the haulage rope which provides propulsion.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Aerial tramways are constructed as *reversible systems*; vehicles shuttling back and forth between two end terminals and propelled by a cable loop which stops and reverses direction when the cabins arrive at the end stations.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Aerial tramways differ from gondola lifts in that gondola lifts are considered *continuous systems* (cabins attached onto a *circulating* haul cable that moves continuously).
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Two-car tramways use a *jig-back* system: a large electric motor is located at the bottom of the tramway so that it effectively pulls one cabin down, using that cabin's weight to help pull the other cabin up.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] A similar system of cables is used in a funicular railway.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The two passenger or cargo cabins, which carry from 4 to over 150 people, are situated at opposite ends of the loops of cable.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Thus, while one is coming up, the other is going down the mountain, and they pass each other midway on the cable span.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Some aerial trams have only one cabin, which lends itself better to systems with small elevation changes along the cable run.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The first design of an aerial lift was by Croatian polymath Fausto Veranzio, and the first operational aerial tram was built in 1644 by Adam Wybe in Gdańsk, Poland.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It was moved by horses and used to move soil over the river to build defences.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It is called the first known cable lift in European history and precedes the invention of steel cables.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It is not known how long this lift was used.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Germany installed the second cable lift 230 years later, now using iron wire cable.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Aerial tramways are sometimes used in mountainous regions to carry ore from a mine located high on the mountain to an ore mill located at a lower elevation.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Ore tramways were common in the early 20th century at the mines in North and South America.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] One can still be seen in the San Juan Mountains of the US state of Colorado.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Another famous use of aerial tramways was at the Kennecott Copper mine in Wrangell-St.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] One of the longest and highest aerial tramway used for mining was built for the *La Mejicana* mine in Chilecito in Argentina, operating between 1906-1927, it carried material between the mine over a height difference of 3,374 m (11,070 ft).
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] While out of service, the stations of the aerial tramway remain a frequent tourist destination.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Other firms entered the mining tramway business, including Otto, Leschen, Breco Ropeways Ltd., Ceretti and Tanfani, and Riblet.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] A major British contributor was Bullivant, which became a constituent of British Ropes in 1924.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] In the beginning of the 20th century, the rise of the middle class and the leisure industry allowed for investment in sight-seeing transport.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Prior to 1893, a combined goods and passenger carrying cableway was installed at Gibraltar.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Initially, its passengers were military personnel.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] An 1893 industry publication said of a two-mile system in Hong Kong that it "is the only wire tramway which has been erected exclusively for the carriage of individuals" (albeit workmen).
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Shortly after, in 1894, a passenger tramway operated across the Tennessee River at Knoxville, Tennessee.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] They were much less expensive to build than the earlier rack railway.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] One of the first aerial trams was at Chamonix, while others in Switzerland, and Garmisch soon followed.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] From this, it was a natural transposition to build ski lifts and chairlifts.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Many aerial tramways were built by Von Roll Ltd. of Switzerland, later acquired by Austrian lift manufacturer Doppelmayr.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Other German, Swiss, and Austrian firms played an important role in the cable car business: Bleichert, Heckel, Pohlig, PHB (Pohlig-Heckel-Bleichert), Garaventa and Waagner-Biró.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Now there are three groups dominating the world market: Doppelmayr Garaventa Group, Leitner Group, and Poma, the last two being owned by one person.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Some aerial tramways have their own propulsion, such as the Lasso Mule or the Josef Mountain Aerial Tramway near Merano, Italy.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] While typically used for ski resorts, aerial tramways have come into use in the urban environment.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The telpherage concept was first publicised in 1883 and several experimental lines were constructed.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It was designed to compete not with railways, but with horses and carts.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The first commercial telpherage line was in Glynde, which is in Sussex, England.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] It was built to connect a newly opened clay pit to the local railway station and opened in 1885.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] There are aerial tramways with double deck cabins.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The Vanoise Express cable car carries 200 people in each cabin at a height of 380 m (1,247 ft) over the Ponturin gorge in France.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The Shinhotaka Ropeway carries 121 people in each cabin at Mount Hotaka in Japan.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] The CabriO cable car to the summit of the Stanserhorn in Switzerland carries 60 persons, with the upper floor accommodating 30 people in the open air.
[src:escalator/aerial-tramway] Despite the introduction of various safety measures (back-up power generators, evacuation plans, etc.) there have been several serious incidents on aerial tramways, some fatal.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] An **airline** is a company that provides a regular service of air transportation for passengers or freight (cargo).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Airlines use aircraft to supply these services.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Many passenger airlines also carry cargo in the belly of their aircraft, while dedicated cargo airlines focus solely on freight transport.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Generally, airlines are recognized with an air operating certificate or license issued by a governmental aviation body.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] These airlines may be scheduled or charter operators.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Airline ownership has seen a shift from mostly personal ownership until the 1930s to government-ownership of major airlines from the 1940s to 1980s and back to large-scale privatization following the mid-1980s.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Since the 1980s, there has been a trend of major airline mergers and the formation of partnerships or alliances for codeshare agreements, in which they both offer and operate the same flight.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The largest alliances are Star Alliance, SkyTeam and Oneworld.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Airline alliances coordinate their passenger service programs (such as lounges and frequent-flyer programs), offer special interline tickets and often engage in extensive codesharing (sometimes systemwide).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] DELAG, *Deutsche Luftschiffahrts-Aktiengesellschaft*, was the world’s first commercial passenger airline.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It was founded on November 16, 1909, and began services in June 1910, providing a regular service until 1935.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] DELAG operated airships manufactured by the Zeppelin Company.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Compagnie générale transaérienne (CGT) was founded on October 10, 1909, making it the oldest airline company, which began cargo operations in April 1911 and began regular passenger operations in March 1913—weekly return fixed-wing flights.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] CGT was the first of the companies that would eventually merge to become Air France.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] A fixed-wing scheduled airline was started in the United States in January 1914.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Petersburg–Tampa Airboat Line was piloted by Tony Jannus and flew from St.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The British airship, HM Airship R34 was the first aircraft of any type to carry passengers across the Atlantic Ocean when on 2 July 1919 it left Scotland, travelled to New York and returned.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Aircraft Transport and Travel (AT&T), formed by George Holt Thomas in 1916 as a fixed-wing airline; via a series of takeovers and mergers, this company is the earliest predecessor company of British Airways.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Using a fleet of former military Airco DH.4A biplanes that had been modified to carry two passengers in the fuselage, it operated relief flights between Folkestone and Ghent, Belgium.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] On July 15, 1919, the company flew a proving flight across the English Channel, despite a lack of support from the British government.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] H Shaw in an Airco DH.9 between RAF Hendon and Paris – Le Bourget Airport, the flight took 2 hours and 30 minutes at £21 per passenger.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] On August 25, 1919, the company used DH.16s to pioneer a regular service from Hounslow Heath Aerodrome to Paris's Le Bourget, the first daily international service in the world.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The airline soon gained a reputation for reliability, despite problems with bad weather, and began to attract European competition.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In November 1919, it won the first British civil airmail contract.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Six Royal Air Force Airco DH.9A aircraft were lent to the company, to operate the airmail service between Hawkinge and Cologne.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1920, they were returned to the Royal Air Force.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Other British competitors were quick to follow – Handley Page Transport was established in 1919 and used the company's converted wartime Type O/400 bombers with a capacity for 12 passengers, to run a London-Paris passenger service.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Société des lignes Latécoère, a predecessor of Air France, later known as Aéropostale, started its first airmail service in late 1924 to Spain.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Société Générale des Transports Aériens was created in late 1919, by the Farman brothers.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It began a weekly service between Paris and Brussels on 22 March 1919, the world's first international commercial aviation service.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Farman F.60 Goliath plane flew scheduled services from Toussus-le-Noble to Kenley, near Croydon, England.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Another early French airline was the Compagnie des Messageries Aériennes, established in 1919 by Louis-Charles Breguet, offering a mail and freight service between Le Bourget Airport, Paris and Lesquin Airport, Lille.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The first German airline to use heavier than air aircraft was Deutsche Luft-Reederei (DLR) established in 1917 which started operating in February 1919.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In its first year, the DLR operated regularly scheduled flights on routes with a combined length of nearly 1000 miles.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] By 1921 the DLR network was more than 3000 km (1865 miles) long, and included destinations in the Netherlands, Scandinavia and the Baltic Republics.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Another important German airline was Junkers Luftverkehr, which began operations in 1921.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It was a division of the aircraft manufacturer Junkers, which became a separate company in 1924.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It operated joint-venture airlines in Austria, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Hungary, Latvia, Norway, Poland, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Dutch airline KLM made its first flight in 1920, and is the oldest airline still using the original name.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Established by aviator Albert Plesman, it was immediately awarded a "Royal" predicate from Queen Wilhelmina.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Its first flight was from Croydon Airport, London to Amsterdam, using a leased DH-16 from Aircraft Transport and Travel, carrying two British journalists and a number of newspapers.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1921, KLM started scheduled services.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In Finland, the charter establishing Aero O/Y (now Finnair) was signed in the city of Helsinki on 12 September 1923.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Junkers F.13 D-335 became the first aircraft of the company, when Aero took delivery of it on 14 March 1924.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The first flight was between Helsinki and Tallinn, capital of Estonia, and it took place on 20 March 1924, one week later.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the Soviet Union, the Chief Administration of the Civil Air Fleet was established in 1921.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] One of its first acts was to help found Deutsch-Russische Luftverkehrs A.G.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] (Deruluft), a German-Russian joint venture to provide air transport from Russia to the West.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Domestic air service began around the same time, when Dobrolyot started operations on 15 July 1923 between Moscow and Nizhni Novgorod.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Since 1932 all operations had been carried under the name Aeroflot.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Early European airlines tended to favor comfort – the passenger cabins were often spacious with luxurious interiors – over speed and efficiency.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The relatively basic navigational capabilities of pilots at the time also meant that delays due to the weather were commonplace.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] By the early 1920s, small airlines were struggling to compete, and there was a movement towards increased rationalization and consolidation.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1924, Imperial Airways was formed from the merger of Instone Air Line Company, British Marine Air Navigation, Daimler Airway and Handley Page Transport, to allow British airlines to compete with stiff competition from French and German airlines that were enjoying heavy government subsidies.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The airline was a pioneer in surveying and opening up air routes across the world to serve far-flung parts of the British Empire and to enhance trade and integration.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The first new airliner ordered by Imperial Airways, was the Handley Page W8f *City of Washington*, delivered on 3 November 1924.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the first year of operation the company carried 11,395 passengers and 212,380 letters.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In April 1925, the film *The Lost World* became the first film to be screened for passengers on a scheduled airliner flight when it was shown on the London-Paris route.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Two French airlines also merged to form Air Union on 1 January 1923.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This later merged with four other French airlines to become Air France, the country's flagship carrier to this day, on 17 May 1933.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Germany's Deutsche Lufthansa was created in 1926 by merger of two airlines, one of them Junkers Luftverkehr.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Lufthansa, due to the Junkers heritage and unlike most other airlines at the time, became a major investor in airlines outside of Europe, providing capital to Varig and Avianca.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] German airliners built by Junkers, Dornier, and Fokker were among the most advanced in the world at the time.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1926, Alan Cobham surveyed a flight route from the UK to Cape Town, South Africa, following this up with another proving flight to Melbourne, Australia.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Other routes to British India and the Far East were also charted and demonstrated at this time.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Regular services to Cairo and Basra began in 1927 and were extended to Karachi in 1929.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The London-Australia service was inaugurated in 1932 with the Handley Page HP 42 airliners.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Further services were opened up to Calcutta, Rangoon, Singapore, Brisbane and Hong Kong passengers departed London on 14 March 1936 following the establishment of a branch from Penang to Hong Kong.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] France began an air mail service to Morocco in 1919 that was bought out in 1927, renamed Aéropostale, and injected with capital to become a major international carrier.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1933, Aéropostale went bankrupt, was nationalized and merged into Air France.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Although Germany lacked colonies, it also began expanding its services globally.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1931, the airship Graf Zeppelin began offering regular scheduled passenger service between Germany and South America, usually every two weeks, which continued until 1937.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1936, the airship Hindenburg entered passenger service and successfully crossed the Atlantic 36 times before crashing at Lakehurst, New Jersey, on 6 May 1937.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1938, a weekly air service from Berlin to Kabul, Afghanistan, started operating.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] From February 1934 until World War II began in 1939, Deutsche Lufthansa operated an airmail service from Stuttgart, Germany via Spain, the Canary Islands and West Africa to Natal in Brazil.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This was the first time an airline flew across an ocean.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] By the end of the 1930s Aeroflot had become the world's largest airline, employing more than 4,000 pilots and 60,000 other service personnel and operating around 3,000 aircraft (of which 75% were considered obsolete by its own standards).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] During the Soviet era Aeroflot was synonymous with Russian civil aviation, as it was the only air carrier.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It became the first airline in the world to operate sustained regular jet services on 15 September 1956 with the Tupolev Tu-104.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Deregulation of the European Union airspace in the early 1990s has had substantial effect on the structure of the industry there.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The shift towards 'budget' airlines on shorter routes has been significant.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Airlines such as EasyJet and Ryanair have often grown at the expense of the traditional national airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] There has also been a trend for these national airlines themselves to be privatized such as has occurred for Aer Lingus and British Airways.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Other national airlines, including Italy's Alitalia, suffered – particularly with the rapid increase of oil prices in early 2008.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Tony Jannus conducted the United States' first scheduled commercial airline flight on January 1, 1914, for the St.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The 23-minute flight traveled between St.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Petersburg, Florida and Tampa, Florida, passing some 50 feet (15 m) above Tampa Bay in Jannus' Benoist XIV wood and muslin biplane flying boat.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Petersburg, who paid $400 for the privilege of sitting on a wooden bench in the open cockpit.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Airboat line operated for about four months, carrying more than 1,200 passengers who paid $5 each.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Chalk's International Airlines claimed to have begun a service between Miami and Bimini in the Bahamas in February 1919.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Lauderdale, Chalk's claimed to be the oldest continuously operating airline in the United States until its closure in 2008.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Following World War I, the United States found itself swamped with aviators.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Many decided to take their war-surplus aircraft on barnstorming campaigns, performing aerobatic maneuvers to woo crowds.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1918, the United States Post Office Department won the financial backing of Congress to begin experimenting with air mail service, initially using Curtiss Jenny aircraft that had been procured by the United States Army Air Service.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Private operators were the first to fly the mail but due to numerous accidents the US Army was tasked with mail delivery.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] During the Army's involvement they proved to be too unreliable and lost their air mail duties.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] By the mid-1920s, the Post Office had developed its own air mail network, based on a transcontinental backbone between New York City and San Francisco.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] To supplement this service, they offered twelve contracts for spur routes to independent bidders.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Some of the carriers that won these routes would, through time and mergers, evolve into Pan Am, Delta Air Lines, Braniff Airways, American Airlines, United Airlines (originally a division of Boeing), Trans World Airlines, Northwest Airlines, and Eastern Air Lines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Service during the early 1920s was sporadic: most airlines at the time were focused on carrying bags of mail.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1925, however, the Ford Motor Company bought out the Stout Aircraft Company and began construction of the all-metal Ford Trimotor, which became the first successful American airliner.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] With a 12-passenger capacity, the Trimotor made passenger service potentially profitable.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Air service was seen as a supplement to rail service in the American transportation network.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] At the same time, Juan Trippe began a crusade to create an air network that would link America to the world, and he achieved this goal through his airline, Pan Am, with a fleet of flying boats that linked Los Angeles to Shanghai and Boston to London.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Pan Am and Northwest Airways (which began flights to Canada in the 1920s) were the only U.S. airlines to go international before the 1940s.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] With the introduction of the Boeing 247 and Douglas DC-3 in the 1930s, the U.S. airline industry was generally profitable, even during the Great Depression.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This trend continued until the beginning of World War II.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] World War II, like World War I, brought new life to the airline industry.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Many airlines in the Allied countries were flush from lease contracts to the military, and foresaw a future explosive demand for civil air transport, for both passengers and cargo.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] They were eager to invest in the newly emerging flagships of air travel such as the Boeing Stratocruiser, Lockheed Constellation, and Douglas DC-6.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Most of these new aircraft were based on American bombers such as the B-29, which had spearheaded research into new technologies such as pressurization.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Most offered increased efficiency from both added speed and greater payload.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Vickers Viscount and Lockheed L-188 Electra inaugurated turboprop transport.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] On 4 October 1958, British Overseas Airways Corporation started transatlantic flights between London Heathrow and New York Idlewild with a Comet 4, and Pan Am followed on 26 October with a Boeing 707 service between New York and Paris.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The next big boost for the airlines would come in the 1970s, when the Boeing 747, McDonnell Douglas DC-10, and Lockheed L-1011 inaugurated widebody ("jumbo jet") service, which is still the standard in international travel.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Tupolev Tu-144 and its Western counterpart, Concorde, made supersonic travel a reality.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Concorde first flew in 1969 and operated through 2003.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In 1972, Airbus began producing Europe's most commercially successful line of airliners to date.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The added efficiencies for these aircraft were often not in speed, but in passenger capacity, payload, and range.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Airbus also features modern electronic cockpits that were common across their aircraft to enable pilots to fly multiple models with minimal cross-training.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The 1978 U.S. airline industry deregulation lowered federally controlled barriers for new airlines just as a downturn in the nation's economy occurred.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] New start-ups entered during the downturn, during which time they found aircraft and funding, contracted hangar and maintenance services, trained new employees, and recruited laid-off staff from other airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Major airlines dominated their routes through aggressive pricing and additional capacity offerings, often swamping new start-ups.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the place of high barriers to entry imposed by regulation, the major airlines implemented an equally high barrier called loss leader pricing.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In this strategy an already established and dominant airline stomps out its competition by lowering airfares on specific routes, below the cost of operating on it, choking out any chance a start-up airline may have.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The industry side effect is an overall drop in revenue and service quality.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Since deregulation in 1978 the average domestic ticket price has dropped by 40%.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] After incurring massive losses, the airlines of the USA relied upon Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings to continue doing business.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] America West Airlines (which has since merged with US Airways) remained a significant survivor from this new entrant era, as dozens, even hundreds, have gone under.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In many ways, the biggest winner in the deregulated environment was the air passenger.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Although not exclusively attributable to deregulation, indeed the U.S. witnessed an explosive growth in demand for air travel.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Many millions who had never or rarely flown before became regular fliers, even joining frequent flyer loyalty programs and receiving free flights and other benefits from their flying.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] New services and higher frequencies meant that business fliers could fly to another city, do business, and return the same day, from almost any point in the country.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Air travel's advantages put long-distance intercity railroad travel and bus lines under pressure, with most of the latter having withered away, whilst the former is still protected under nationalization through the continuing existence of Amtrak.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] By the 1980s, almost half of the total flying in the world took place in the U.S., and today the domestic industry operates over 10,000 daily departures nationwide.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Toward the end of the century, a new style of low cost airline emerged, offering a no-frills product at a lower price.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Southwest Airlines, JetBlue, AirTran Airways, Skybus Airlines and other low-cost carriers began to represent a serious challenge to the so-called "legacy airlines", as did their low-cost counterparts in many other countries.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Their commercial viability represented a serious competitive threat to the legacy carriers.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] However, of these, ATA and Skybus have since ceased operations.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Increasingly since 1978, US airlines have been reincorporated and spun off by newly created and internally led management companies, and thus becoming nothing more than operating units and subsidiaries with limited financially decisive control.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Among some of these holding companies and parent companies which are relatively well known, are the UAL Corporation, along with the AMR Corporation, among a long list of airline holding companies sometime recognized worldwide.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Thus the last 50 years of the airline industry have varied from reasonably profitable, to devastatingly depressed.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] As the first major market to deregulate the industry in 1978, U.S. airlines have experienced more turbulence than almost any other country or region.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In fact, no U.S. legacy carrier survived bankruptcy-free.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Congress passed the Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act (P.L.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] 107–42) in response to a severe liquidity crisis facing the already-troubled airline industry in the aftermath of the September 11 attacks.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Through the ATSB Congress sought to provide cash infusions to carriers for both the cost of the four-day federal shutdown of the airlines and the incremental losses incurred through December 31, 2001, as a result of the terrorist attacks.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This resulted in the first government bailout of the 21st century.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Between 2000 and 2005 US airlines lost $30 billion with wage cuts of over $15 billion and 100,000 employees laid off.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In recognition of the essential national economic role of a healthy aviation system, Congress authorized partial compensation of up to $5 billion in cash subject to review by the U.S.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Department of Transportation and up to $10 billion in loan guarantees subject to review by a newly created Air Transportation Stabilization Board (ATSB).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The applications to DOT for reimbursements were subjected to rigorous multi-year reviews not only by DOT program personnel but also by the Government Accountability Office and the DOT Inspector General.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Ultimately, the federal government provided $4.6 billion in one-time, subject-to-income-tax cash payments to 427 U.S. air carriers, with no provision for repayment, essentially a gift from the taxpayers.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] (Passenger carriers operating scheduled service received approximately $4 billion, subject to tax.) In addition, the ATSB approved loan guarantees to six airlines totaling approximately $1.6 billion.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Treasury Department show that the government recouped the $1.6 billion and a profit of $339 million from the fees, interest and purchase of discounted airline stock associated with loan guarantees.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] As of May 2018 the four largest major carriers controlled 70% of the U.S. passenger market.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Although Philippine Airlines (PAL) was officially founded on February 26, 1941, its license to operate as an airliner was derived from merged Philippine Aerial Taxi Company (PATCO) established by mining magnate Emmanuel N.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Bachrach on 3 December 1930, making it Asia's oldest scheduled carrier still in operation.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Commercial air service commenced three weeks later from Manila to Baguio, making it Asia's first airline route.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Bachrach's death in 1937 paved the way for its eventual merger with Philippine Airlines in March 1941 and made it Asia's oldest airline.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It is also the oldest airline in Asia still operating under its current name.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Bachrach's majority share in PATCO was bought by beer magnate Andres R.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Soriano in 1939 upon the advice of General Douglas MacArthur and later merged with newly formed Philippine Airlines with PAL as the surviving entity.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Soriano has controlling interest in both airlines before the merger.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] PAL restarted service on 15 March 1941, with a single Beech Model 18 NPC-54 aircraft, which started its daily services between Manila (from Nielson Field) and Baguio, later to expand with larger aircraft such as the DC-3 and Vickers Viscount.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In Japan, Japan Air Transport was established in 1928 as the national flag carrier.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Upon the completion of Haneda Airport in 1931, it became the airline's hub.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The airline initially operated domestic routes such as Tokyo–Osaka and Osaka–Fukuoka.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In September 1929, it opened its first overseas route, which connected Fukuoka to Dalian in the Kwantung Leased Territory via Seoul and Pyongyang in Japanese Korea.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] After Japan established the puppet state of Manchukuo, the airline opened routes to major cities within this territory.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The company was reorganized as Japan Airways in 1938.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] During the Second World War, it operated routes to various Japanese-occupied territories and Thailand.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The company was dissolved immediately after the war, as civil aviation was prohibited by the Allied Occupation Forces.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Civil aviation in Japan did not resume until the founding of Japan Airlines in 1951.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Cathay Pacific was one of the first airlines to be launched among the other Asian countries in 1946.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The license to operate as an airliner was granted by the federal government body after reviewing the necessity at the national assembly.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Hanjin occupies the largest ownership of Korean Air as well as few low-budget airlines as of now.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Korean Air is one of the four founders of SkyTeam, which was established in 2000.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Asiana Airlines, launched in 1988, joined Star Alliance in 2003.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] India was also one of the first countries to embrace civil aviation.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] One of the first Asian airline companies was Air India, which was founded as Tata Airlines in 1932, a division of Tata Sons Ltd.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The airline was founded by India's leading industrialist, JRD Tata.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Tata himself flew a single engined De Havilland Puss Moth carrying air mail (postal mail of Imperial Airways) from Karachi to Bombay via Ahmedabad.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The aircraft continued to Madras via Bellary piloted by Royal Air Force pilot Nevill Vintcent.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Tata Airlines was also one of the world's first major airlines which began its operations without any support from the Government.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] With the outbreak of World War II, the airline presence in Asia came to a relative halt, with many new flag carriers donating their aircraft for military aid and other uses.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Following the end of the war in 1945, regular commercial service was restored in India and Tata Airlines became a public limited company on 29 July 1946, under the name Air India.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] After the independence of India, 49% of the airline was acquired by the Government of India.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In return, the airline was granted status to operate international services from India as the designated flag carrier under the name Air India International.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] On 31 July 1946, a chartered Philippine Airlines (PAL) DC-4 ferried 40 American servicemen to Oakland, California, from Nielson Airport in Makati with stops in Guam, Wake Island, Johnston Atoll and Honolulu, Hawaii, making PAL the first Asian airline to cross the Pacific Ocean.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] A regular service between Manila and San Francisco was started in December.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] It was during this year that the airline was designated as the flag carrier of Philippines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] During the era of decolonization, newly born Asian countries started to embrace air transport.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] All the previous airlines started regular operations well before World War II.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Puerto Rican commercial airlines such as Prinair, Oceanair, Fina Air and Vieques Air Link came much after the second world war, as did several others from other countries like Mexico's Interjet and Volaris, Venezuela's Aserca Airlines and others.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The air travel market has evolved rapidly over recent years in Latin America.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Some industry estimates indicated in 2011 that over 2,000 new aircraft will begin service over the next five years in this region.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] These airlines serve domestic flights within their countries, as well as connections within Latin America and also overseas flights to North America, Europe, Australia, and Asia.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Only four airline groups – Avianca, Panama's Copa, Mexico's Volaris, and LATAM Airlines – have international subsidiaries and cover many destinations within the Americas as well as major hubs in other continents.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] LATAM with Chile as the central operation along with Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Brazil and Argentina and formerly with some operations in the Dominican Republic.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The Avianca group has its main operation in Colombia based around the hub in Bogotá, Colombia, as well as subsidiaries in various Latin American countries with hubs in San Salvador, El Salvador, as well as Lima, Peru, with a smaller operation in Ecuador.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Copa has subsidiaries Copa Airlines Colombia and Wingo, both in Colombia, while Volaris of Mexico has Volaris Costa Rica and Volaris El Salvador, and the Irelandia group formerly included Viva Aerobus of Mexico, Viva Colombia and Viva Air Peru.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Many countries have national airlines that the government owns and operates.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Fully private airlines are subject to much government regulation for economic, political, and safety concerns.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] For instance, governments often intervene to halt airline labor actions to protect the free flow of people, communications, and goods between different regions without compromising safety.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The United States, Australia, and to a lesser extent Brazil, Mexico, India, the United Kingdom, and Japan have "deregulated" their airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the past, these governments dictated airfares, route networks, and other operational requirements for each airline.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Since deregulation, airlines have been largely free to negotiate their own operating arrangements with different airports, enter and exit routes easily, and to levy airfares and supply flights according to market demand.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The entry barriers for new airlines are lower in a deregulated market, and so the U.S. has seen hundreds of airlines start up (sometimes for only a brief operating period).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This has produced far greater competition than before deregulation in most markets.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The added competition, together with pricing freedom, means that new entrants often take market share with highly reduced rates that, to a limited degree, full service airlines must match.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] This is a major constraint on profitability for established carriers, which tend to have a higher cost base.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] As a result, profitability in a deregulated market is uneven for most airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] These forces have caused some major airlines to go out of business, in addition to most of the poorly established new entrants.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the United States, the airline industry is dominated by four large firms.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Because of industry consolidation, after fuel prices dropped considerably in 2015, very little of the savings were passed on to consumers.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Groups such as the International Civil Aviation Organization establish worldwide standards for safety and other vital concerns.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Most international air traffic is regulated by bilateral agreements between countries, which designate specific carriers to operate on specific routes.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] The model of such an agreement was the Bermuda Agreement between the US and UK following World War II, which designated airports to be used for transatlantic flights and gave each government the authority to nominate carriers to operate routes.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Bilateral agreements are based on the "freedoms of the air", a group of generalized traffic rights ranging from the freedom to overfly a country to the freedom to provide domestic flights within a country (a very rarely granted right known as cabotage).
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Most agreements permit airlines to fly from their home country to designated airports in the other country: some also extend the freedom to provide continuing service to a third country, or to another destination in the other country while carrying passengers from overseas.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] In the 1990s, "open skies" agreements became more common.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] These agreements take many of these regulatory powers from state governments and open up international routes to further competition.
[src:escalator/airline-p01] Open skies agreements have met some criticism, particularly within the European Union, whose airlines would be at a comparative disadvantage with the United States' because of cabotage restrictions.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In 2017, 4.1 billion passengers have been carried by airlines in 41.9 million commercial scheduled flights (an average payload of 98 passengers), for 7.75 trillion passenger kilometers (an average trip of 1890 km) over 45,091 airline routes served globally.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In 2016, air transport generated $704.4 billion of revenue in 2016, employed 10.2 million workers, supported 65.5 million jobs and $2.7 trillion of economic activity: 3.6% of the global GDP.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In July 2016, the total weekly airline capacity was 181.1 billion Available Seat Kilometers (+6.9% compared to July 2015): 57.6bn in Asia-Pacific, 47.7bn in Europe, 46.2bn in North America, 12.2bn in Middle East, 12.0bn in Latin America and 5.4bn in Africa.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Thus all but a small percentage of the income from ticket sales is paid out to a wide variety of external providers or internal cost centers.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Moreover, the industry is structured so that airlines often act as tax collectors.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airline fuel is untaxed because of a series of treaties existing between countries.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Ticket prices include a number of fees, taxes and surcharges beyond the control of airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines are also responsible for enforcing government regulations.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] If airlines carry passengers without proper documentation on an international flight, they are responsible for returning them back to the original country.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Analysis of the 1992–1996 period shows that every player in the air transport chain is far more profitable than the airlines, who collect and pass through fees and revenues to them from ticket sales.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] While airlines as a whole earned 6% return on capital employed (2–3.5% less than the cost of capital), airports earned 10%, catering companies 10–13%, handling companies 11–14%, aircraft lessors 15%, aircraft manufacturers 16%, and global distribution companies more than 30%.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] There has been continuing cost competition from low cost airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many companies emulate Southwest Airlines in various respects.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The lines between full-service and low-cost airlines have become blurred – e.g., with most "full service" airlines introducing baggage check fees despite Southwest not doing so.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many airlines in the U.S. and elsewhere have experienced business difficulty.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] U.S. airlines that have declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy since 1990 have included American Airlines, Continental Airlines (twice), Delta Air Lines, Northwest Airlines, Pan Am, United Airlines and US Airways (twice).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Where an airline has established an engineering base at an airport, then there may be considerable economic advantages in using that same airport as a preferred focus (or "hub") for its scheduled flights.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Fuel hedging is a contractual tool used by transportation companies like airlines to reduce their exposure to volatile and potentially rising fuel costs.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Several low-cost carriers such as Southwest Airlines adopt this practice.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Southwest is credited with maintaining strong business profits between 1999 and the early 2000s due to its fuel hedging policy.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many other airlines are replicating Southwest's hedging policy to control their fuel costs.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] An average US major Boeing 757-200 flies 1,252 miles (2,015 km) stages 11.3 block hours per day and costs $2,550 per block hour: $923 of ownership, $590 of maintenance, $548 of fuel and $489 of crew; or $13.34 per 186 seats per block hour.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For a Boeing 737-500, a low-cost carrier like Southwest have lower operating costs at $1,526 than a full service one like United at $2,974, and higher productivity with 399,746 ASM per day against 264,284, resulting in a unit cost of 0.38 $cts/ASM against 1.13 $cts/ASM.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] McKinsey observes that "newer technology, larger aircraft, and increasingly efficient operations continually drive down the cost of running an airline", from nearly 40 US cents per ASK at the beginning of the jet age, to just above 10 cents since 2000.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Those improvements were passed onto the customer due to high competition: fares have been falling throughout the history of airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines assign prices to their services in an attempt to maximize profitability.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The pricing of airline tickets has become increasingly complicated over the years and is now largely determined by computerized yield management systems.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Because of the complications in scheduling flights and maintaining profitability, airlines have many loopholes that can be used by the knowledgeable traveler.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many of these airfare secrets are becoming more and more known to the general public, so airlines are forced to make constant adjustments.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Most airlines use differentiated pricing, a form of price discrimination, to sell air services at varying prices simultaneously to different segments.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Factors influencing the price include the days remaining until departure, the booked load factor, the forecast of total demand by price point, competitive pricing in force, and variations by day of week of departure and by time of day.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Carriers often accomplish this by dividing each cabin of the aircraft (first, business and economy) into a number of travel classes for pricing purposes.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] A complicating factor is that of origin-destination control ("O&D control").
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Someone purchasing a ticket from Melbourne to Sydney (as an example) for A$200 is competing with someone else who wants to fly Melbourne to Los Angeles through Sydney on the same flight, and who is willing to pay A$1400.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Should the airline prefer the $1400 passenger, or the $200 passenger plus a possible Sydney-Los Angeles passenger willing to pay $1300?
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines have to make hundreds of thousands of similar pricing decisions daily.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The intense nature of airfare pricing has led to the term "fare war" to describe efforts by airlines to undercut other airlines on competitive routes.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Through computers, new airfares can be published quickly and efficiently to the airlines' sales channels.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For this purpose the airlines use the Airline Tariff Publishing Company (ATPCO), who distribute latest fares for more than 500 airlines to Computer Reservation Systems across the world.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The extent of these pricing phenomena is strongest in "legacy" carriers.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In contrast, low fare carriers usually offer pre-announced and simplified price structure, and sometimes quote prices for each leg of a trip separately.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Computers also allow airlines to predict, with some accuracy, how many passengers will actually fly after making a reservation to fly.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] This is especially crucial during tough economic times as airlines undertake massive cuts to ticket prices to retain demand.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Over January/February 2018, the cheapest airline surveyed by price comparator rome2rio was now-defunct Tigerair Australia with $0.06/km followed by AirAsia X with $0.07/km, while the most expensive was Charterlines, Inc. with $1.26/km followed by Buddha Air with $1.18/km.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For the IATA, the global airline industry revenue was $754 billion in 2017 for a $38.4 billion collective profit, and should rise by 10.7% to $834 billion in 2018 for a $33.8 billion profit forecast, down by 12% due to rising jet fuel and labor costs.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The demand for air transport will be less elastic for longer flights than for shorter flights, and more elastic for leisure travel than for business travel.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines often have a strong seasonality, with traffic low in winter and peaking in summer.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In Europe the most extreme market are the Greek islands with July/August having more than ten times the winter traffic, as Jet2 is the most seasonal among low-cost carriers with July having seven times the January traffic, whereas legacy carriers are much less with only 85/115% variability.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airline financing is quite complex, since airlines are highly leveraged operations.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] A second financial issue is that of hedging oil and fuel purchases, which are usually second only to labor in its relative cost to the company.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] However, with the current high fuel prices it has become the largest cost to an airline.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Legacy airlines, compared with new entrants, have been hit harder by rising fuel prices partly due to the running of older, less fuel efficient aircraft.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] While hedging instruments can be expensive, they can easily pay for themselves many times over in periods of increasing fuel costs, such as in the 2000–2005 period.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In view of the congestion apparent at many international airports, the ownership of slots at certain airports (the right to take-off or land an aircraft at a particular time of day or night) has become a significant tradable asset for many airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Clearly take-off slots at popular times of the day can be critical in attracting the more profitable business traveler to a given airline's flight and in establishing a competitive advantage against a competing airline.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] If a particular city has two or more airports, market forces will tend to attract the less profitable routes, or those on which competition is weakest, to the less congested airport, where slots are likely to be more available and therefore cheaper.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For example, Reagan National Airport attracts profitable routes due partly to its congestion, leaving less-profitable routes to Baltimore-Washington International Airport and Dulles International Airport.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Other factors, such as surface transport facilities and onward connections, will also affect the relative appeal of different airports and some long-distance flights may need to operate from the one with the longest runway.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For example, LaGuardia Airport is the preferred airport for most of Manhattan due to its proximity, while long-distance routes must use John F.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Kennedy International Airport's longer runways.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The first airline alliance was formed in the 1930s when Pan Am and its subsidiary, Panair do Brasil, agreed to codeshare routes in Latin America when they overlapped with each other.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Codesharing involves one airline selling tickets for another airline's flights under its own airline code.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] An early example of this was Japan Airlines' (JAL) codesharing partnership with Aeroflot in the 1960s on Tokyo–Moscow flights; Aeroflot operated the flights using Aeroflot aircraft, but JAL sold tickets for the flights as if they were JAL flights.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Another example was the Austrian–Sabena partnership on the Vienna–Brussels–New York/JFK route during the late '60s, using a Sabena Boeing 707 with Austrian livery.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Since airline reservation requests are often made by city-pair (such as "show me flights from Chicago to Düsseldorf"), an airline that can codeshare with another airline for a variety of routes might be able to be listed as indeed offering a Chicago–Düsseldorf flight.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The passenger is advised however, that airline no.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] 1 operates the flight from say Chicago to Amsterdam (for example), and airline no.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] 2 operates the continuing flight (on a different airplane, sometimes from another terminal) to Düsseldorf.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Thus the primary rationale for code sharing is to expand one's service offerings in city-pair terms to increase sales.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] A more recent development is the airline alliance, which became prevalent in the late 1990s.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] These alliances can act as virtual mergers to get around government restrictions.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The largest are Star Alliance, SkyTeam and Oneworld, and these accounted for over 60% of global commercial air traffic as of 2015.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Alliances of airlines coordinate their passenger service programs (such as lounges and frequent-flyer programs), offer special interline tickets and often engage in extensive codesharing (sometimes systemwide).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] These are increasingly integrated business combinations—sometimes including cross-equity arrangements—in which products, service standards, schedules, and airport facilities are standardized and combined for higher efficiency.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] One of the first airlines to start an alliance with another airline was KLM, who partnered with Northwest Airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Both airlines later entered the SkyTeam alliance after the fusion of KLM and Air France in 2004.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Often the companies combine IT operations, or purchase fuel and aircraft as a bloc to achieve higher bargaining power.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] However, the alliances have been most successful at purchasing invisible supplies and services, such as fuel.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines usually prefer to purchase items visible to their passengers to differentiate themselves from local competitors.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] If an airline's main domestic competitor flies Boeing airliners, then the airline may prefer to use Airbus aircraft regardless of what the rest of the alliance chooses.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The world's largest airlines can be defined in several ways.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] As of 2019, American Airlines Group was the largest by fleet size, passengers carried and revenue passenger mile.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Delta Air Lines was the largest by revenue, assets value and market capitalization.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Lufthansa Group was the largest by number of employees, FedEx Express by freight ton-kilometers, Turkish Airlines by number of countries served and UPS Airlines by number of destinations served (though United Airlines was the largest passenger airline by number of destinations served).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Historically, air travel has survived largely through state support, whether in the form of equity or subsidies.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The airline industry as a whole has made a cumulative loss during its 100-year history.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] One argument is that positive externalities, such as higher growth due to global mobility, outweigh the microeconomic losses and justify continuing government intervention.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] A historically high level of government intervention in the airline industry can be seen as part of a wider political consensus on strategic forms of transport, such as highways and railways, both of which receive public funding in most parts of the world.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Although many countries continue to operate state-owned or parastatal airlines, many large airlines today are privately owned and are therefore governed by microeconomic principles to maximize shareholder profit.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In December 1991, the collapse of Pan Am, an airline often credited for shaping the international airline industry, highlighted the financial complexities faced by major airline companies.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Following the 1978 deregulation, U.S. carriers did not manage to make an aggregate profit for 12 years in 31, including four years where combined losses amounted to $10 billion, but rebounded with eight consecutive years of profits since 2010, including its four with over $10 billion profits.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] They drop loss-making routes, avoid fare wars and market share battles, limit capacity growth, add hub feed with regional jets to increase their profitability.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] They change schedules to create more connections, buy used aircraft, reduce international frequencies and leverage partnerships to optimize capacities and benefit from overseas connectivity.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Aircraft engines emit noise pollution, gases and particulate emissions, and contribute to global dimming.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Growth of the industry in recent years raised a number of ecological questions.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Domestic air transport grew in China at 15.5 percent annually from 2001 to 2006.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The rate of air travel globally increased at 3.7 percent per year over the same time.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In the EU greenhouse gas emissions from aviation increased by 87% between 1990 and 2006.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Without even pressure from "green activists", targeting lower ticket prices, generally, airlines do what is possible to cut the fuel consumption (and gas emissions connected therewith).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Further, according to some reports, it can be concluded that the last piston-powered aircraft were as fuel-efficient as the average jet in 2005.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Despite continuing efficiency improvements from the major aircraft manufacturers, the expanding demand for global air travel has resulted in growing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In 2009, it was calculated that the aviation sector, including U.S. domestic and global international travel, make approximately 1.6 percent of global anthropogenic GHG emissions per annum.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] That year, North America accounts for nearly 40 percent of the world's GHG emissions from aviation fuel use.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] CO2 emissions from the jet fuel burned per passenger on an average 3,200 kilometers (2,000 mi) airline flight is about 353 kilograms (776 pounds).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Loss of natural habitat potential associated with the jet fuel burned per passenger on a 3,200 kilometers (2,000 mi) airline flight is estimated to be 250 square meters (2700 square feet).
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In the context of climate change and peak oil, there is a debate about possible taxation of air travel and the inclusion of aviation in an emissions trading scheme, with a view to ensuring that the total external costs of aviation are taken into account.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In 2008 it was reported in the *Washington Post* that the airline industry is responsible for about 11 percent of greenhouse gases emitted by the U.S. transportation sector.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Boeing estimated that biofuels could reduce flight-related greenhouse-gas emissions by 60 to 80 percent.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The solution put forth at the time would be to blend algae fuels with existing jet fuel: but so far this has yet to happen.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] There are projects on electric aircraft, and some of which are fully operational as of 2013.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Each operator of a scheduled or charter flight uses an airline call sign when communicating with airports or air traffic control.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] For example, British Airways uses a *Speedbird* call-sign, named after the logo of one of its predecessors, BOAC, while SkyEurope used *Relax*.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The various types of airline personnel include flight crew, responsible for the operation of the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines follow a corporate structure where each broad area of operations (such as maintenance, flight operations (including flight safety), and passenger service) is supervised by a vice president.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Larger airlines often appoint vice presidents to oversee each of the airline's hubs as well.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airlines employ lawyers to deal with regulatory procedures and other administrative tasks.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The pattern of ownership has been privatized since the mid-1980s, that is, the ownership has gradually changed from governments to private and individual sectors or organizations.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] This occurs as regulators permit greater freedom and non-government ownership, in steps that are usually decades apart.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] This pattern is not seen for all airlines in all regions.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many major airlines operating between the 1940s and 1980s were government-owned or government-established.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] However, most airlines from the earliest days of air travel in the 1920s and 1930s were personal businesses.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Growth rates are not consistent in all regions, but countries with a deregulated airline industry have more competition and greater pricing freedom.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] This results in lower fares and sometimes dramatic spurts in traffic growth.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The U.S., Australia, Canada, Japan, Brazil, India and other markets exhibit this trend.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] The industry has been observed to be cyclical in its financial performance.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Four or five years of poor earnings precede five or six years of improvement.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] But profitability even in the good years is generally low, in the range of 2–3% net profit after interest and tax.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In times of profit, airlines lease new generations of airplanes and upgrade services in response to higher demand.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Since 1980, the industry has not earned back the cost of capital during the best of times.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Conversely, in bad times losses can be dramatically worse.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Warren Buffett in 1999 said "the money that had been made since the dawn of aviation by all of this country's airline companies was zero.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] As in many mature industries, consolidation is a trend.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Airline groupings may consist of limited bilateral partnerships, long-term, multi-faceted alliances between carriers, equity arrangements, mergers, or takeovers.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Since governments often restrict ownership and merger between companies in different countries, most consolidation takes place within a country.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] By 1990, nearly 200 airlines in the U.S. had merged, been taken over, or gone out of business since the Airline Deregulation Act in 1978.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] Many international airline managers are lobbying their governments to permit greater consolidation to achieve higher economy and efficiency.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] In addition, there are several cargo-only airlines.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] This can involve specialized aircraft, like those with large cargo doors and reinforced floors, or modifying passenger planes for cargo-only flights.
[src:escalator/airline-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, some passenger airlines temporarily converted their planes for cargo-only flights to meet increased demand for freight transport.
[src:escalator/airliner] An **airliner** is a type of airplane for transporting passengers and air cargo.
[src:escalator/airliner] Such aircraft are most often operated by airlines.
[src:escalator/airliner] The modern and most common variant of the airliner is a jet powered aircraft with a long, tube-shaped fuselage.
[src:escalator/airliner] The largest of them are wide-body jets which are also called twin-aisle because they generally have two separate aisles running from the front to the back of the passenger cabin.
[src:escalator/airliner] These are usually used for long-haul flights between airline hubs and major cities.
[src:escalator/airliner] A smaller, more common class of airliners is the narrow-body or single-aisle.
[src:escalator/airliner] These are generally used for short to medium-distance flights with fewer passengers than their wide-body counterparts.
[src:escalator/airliner] Regional airliners typically seat fewer than 100 passengers and may be powered by turbofans or turboprops.
[src:escalator/airliner] These airliners are the non-mainline counterparts to the larger aircraft operated by the major carriers, legacy carriers, and flag carriers, and are used to feed traffic into the large airline hubs.
[src:escalator/airliner] These regional routes then form the spokes of a hub-and-spoke air transport model.
[src:escalator/airliner] The lightest aircraft are short-haul regional feeder airliner type aircraft that carry a small number of passengers are called commuter aircraft, commuterliners, feederliners, and air taxis, depending on their size, engines, how they are marketed, region of the world, and seating configurations.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Beechcraft 1900, for example, has only 19 seats.
[src:escalator/airliner] When the Wright brothers made the world's first sustained heavier-than-air flight, they laid the foundation for what would become a major transport industry.
[src:escalator/airliner] Their flight, performed in the Wright Flyer during 1903, was just 11 years before what is often defined as the world's first airliner.
[src:escalator/airliner] By the 1960s, airliners had expanded capabilities, making a significant impact on global society, economics, and politics.
[src:escalator/airliner] During 1913, Igor Sikorsky developed the first large multi-engine airplane, the Russky Vityaz.
[src:escalator/airliner] This aircraft was subsequently refined into the more practical Ilya Muromets, being furnished with dual controls for a pilot and copilot and a comfortable cabin with a lavatory, cabin heating and lighting.
[src:escalator/airliner] This large four-engine biplane was further adapted into an early bomber aircraft, preceding subsequent transport and bomber aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] It first flew on 10 December 1913 and took off for its first demonstration flight with 16 passengers aboard on 25 February 1914.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, it was never used as a commercial airliner due to the onset of the First World War which led to military applications being prioritised.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 1919, shortly after the end of the First World War, large numbers of ex-military aircraft flooded the market.
[src:escalator/airliner] One such aircraft was the French Farman F.60 Goliath, which had originally been designed as a long-range heavy bomber; a number were converted for commercial use into passenger airliners starting in 1919, being able to accommodate a maximum of 14 seated passengers.
[src:escalator/airliner] Initially, several publicity flights were made, including one on 8 February 1919, when the Goliath flew 12 passengers from Toussus-le-Noble to RAF Kenley, near Croydon, despite having no permission from the British authorities to land.
[src:escalator/airliner] Dozens of early airlines subsequently procured the type.
[src:escalator/airliner] One high-profile flight, made on 11 August 1919, involved an F.60 flying eight passengers and a ton of supplies from Paris via Casablanca and Mogador to Koufa, 180 km (110 mi) north of Saint-Louis, Senegal, flying more than 4,500 km (2,800 mi).
[src:escalator/airliner] Another important airliner built in 1919 was the Airco DH.16; a redesigned Airco DH.9A with a wider fuselage to accommodate an enclosed cabin seating four passengers, plus pilot in an open cockpit.
[src:escalator/airliner] In March 1919, the prototype first flew at Hendon Aerodrome.
[src:escalator/airliner] Nine aircraft were built, all but one being delivered to the nascent airline, Aircraft Transport and Travel, which used the first aircraft for pleasure flying, and on 25 August 1919, it inaugurated the first scheduled international airline service from London to Paris.
[src:escalator/airliner] One aircraft was sold to the River Plate Aviation Company in Argentina, to operate a cross-river service between Buenos Aires and Montevideo.
[src:escalator/airliner] Meanwhile, the competing Vickers converted its successful First World War era bomber, the Vickers Vimy, into a civilian version, the Vimy Commercial.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was redesigned with a larger-diameter fuselage (largely of spruce plywood), and first flew from the Joyce Green airfield in Kent on 13 April 1919.
[src:escalator/airliner] The world's first all-metal transport aircraft was the Junkers F.13, which also made its first flight in 1919.
[src:escalator/airliner] Junkers marketed the aircraft towards business travellers and commercial operators, and European entrepreneurs bought examples for their private use and business trips.
[src:escalator/airliner] Over 300 Junkers F 13s were built between 1919 and 1932.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Dutch Fokker company produced the Fokker F.II, then the enlarged F.III.
[src:escalator/airliner] These were used by the Dutch airline KLM, including on its Amsterdam-London service in 1921.
[src:escalator/airliner] A relatively reliable aircraft for the era, the Fokkers were flying to destinations across Europe, including Bremen, Brussels, Hamburg, and Paris.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Handley Page company in Britain produced the Handley Page Type W, its first civil transport aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] It housed two crew in an open cockpit and 15 passengers in an enclosed cabin.
[src:escalator/airliner] Powered by two 450 hp (340 kW) Napier Lion engines, the prototype first flew on 4 December 1919, shortly after it was displayed at the 1919 Paris Air Show at Le Bourget.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was ordered by the Belgian firm Sabena, a further ten Type Ws were produced under license in Belgium by SABCA.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 1921 the Air Ministry ordered three aircraft, built as the W.8b, for use by Handley Page Transport, and later by Imperial Airways, on services to Paris and Brussels.
[src:escalator/airliner] In France, the Bleriot-SPAD S.33 was introduced during the early 1920s.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was commercially successful, initially serving the Paris-London route, and later on continental routes.
[src:escalator/airliner] The enclosed cabin could carry four passengers with an extra seat in the cockpit.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was further developed into the Blériot-SPAD S.46.
[src:escalator/airliner] Throughout the 1920s, companies in Britain and France were at the forefront of the civil airliner industry.
[src:escalator/airliner] By 1921, the capacity of airliners needed to be increased to achieve more favourable economics.
[src:escalator/airliner] The English company de Havilland, built the 10-passenger DH.29 monoplane, while starting work on the design of the DH.32, an eight-seater biplane with a more economical but less powerful Rolls-Royce Eagle engine.
[src:escalator/airliner] For more capacity, DH.32 development was replaced by the DH.34 biplane, accommodating 10 passengers.
[src:escalator/airliner] A commercially successful aircraft, Daimler Airway ordered a batch of nine.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Ford Trimotor had two engines mounted on the wings and one in the nose, and a slabsided body, it carried eight passengers and was produced from 1925 to 1933.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was an important early airliner in America.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was used by the predecessor to Trans World Airlines, and by other airlines long after production ceased.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Trimotor helped to popularise numerous aspects of modern aviation infrastructure, including paved runways, passenger terminals, hangars, airmail, and radio navigation.
[src:escalator/airliner] Pan Am opened up transoceanic service in the late 1920s and early 1930s, based on a series of large seaplanes – the Sikorsky S-38 through Sikorsky S-42.
[src:escalator/airliner] By the 1930s, the airliner industry had matured and large consolidated national airlines were established with regular international services that spanned the globe, including Imperial Airways in Britain, Lufthansa in Germany, KLM in the Netherlands, and United Airlines in America.
[src:escalator/airliner] Multi-engined aircraft were now capable of transporting dozens of passengers in comfort.
[src:escalator/airliner] During the 1930s, the British de Havilland Dragon emerged as a short-haul, low-capacity airliner.
[src:escalator/airliner] Its relatively simple design could carry six passengers, each with 45 lb (20 kg) of luggage, on the London-Paris route on a fuel consumption of 13 gal (49 L) per hour.
[src:escalator/airliner] The DH.84 Dragon entered worldwide service.
[src:escalator/airliner] During early August 1934, one performed the first non-stop flight between the Canadian mainland and Britain in 30 hours 55 minutes, although the intended destination had originally been Baghdad in Iraq.
[src:escalator/airliner] British production of the Dragon ended in favour of the de Havilland Dragon Rapide, a faster and more comfortable successor.
[src:escalator/airliner] By November 1934, series production of the Dragon Rapide had commenced.
[src:escalator/airliner] De Havilland invested into advanced features including elongated rear windows, cabin heating, thickened wing tips, and a strengthened airframe for a higher gross weight of 5,500 lb (2,500 kg).
[src:escalator/airliner] Later aircraft were amongst the first airliners to be fitted with flaps for improved landing performance, along with downwards-facing recognition light and metal propellers, which were often retrofitted to older aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was also used in military roles; civil Dragon Rapides were impressed into military service during the Second World War.
[src:escalator/airliner] Metal airliners came into service in the 1930s.
[src:escalator/airliner] In the United States, the Boeing 247, and the 14-passenger Douglas DC-2, flew during the first half of the decade, while the more powerful, faster, 21–32 passenger Douglas DC-3 first appeared in 1935.
[src:escalator/airliner] DC-3s were produced in quantity for the Second World War and were sold as surplus afterward, becoming widespread within the commercial sector.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was one of first airliners to be profitable without the support of postal or government subsidies.
[src:escalator/airliner] Long-haul flights were expanded during the 1930s as Pan American Airways and Imperial Airways competed on transatlantic travel using fleets of flying boats, such as the British Short Empire and the American Boeing 314.
[src:escalator/airliner] Imperial Airways' order for 28 Empire flying boats was viewed by some as a bold gamble.
[src:escalator/airliner] At the time, flying boats were the only practical means of building aircraft of such size and weight as land-based aircraft would have unfeasibly poor field performance.
[src:escalator/airliner] One Boeing 314, registration NC18602, became the first commercial plane to circumnavigate the globe during December 1941 and January 1942.
[src:escalator/airliner] For British use, multi-engine aircraft types were allegedly split between the US for military transport aircraft and the UK for heavy bombers.
[src:escalator/airliner] That such a policy was suggested or implemented have been disputed, at least by Sir Peter Masefield.
[src:escalator/airliner] British aircraft manufacturers were tied up to fulfill military requirements, and had no free capacity to address other matters though the war.
[src:escalator/airliner] After a brief contest, the Type I design was given to the Bristol Aeroplane Company, building on a "100 ton bomber" submission.
[src:escalator/airliner] This evolved into the Bristol Brabazon but this project folded in 1951 as BOAC lost interest and the first aircraft needed a costly wing re-design to accommodate the Bristol Proteus engine.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Type II was split between the de Havilland Dove and Airspeed Ambassador conventional piston designs, and the Vickers model powered by newly developed turboprops: first flown in 1948, the VC.2 Viceroy was the first turboprop design to enter service; a commercial success with 445 Viscounts built.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Type III requirement led to the conventional Avro Tudor and the more ambitious Bristol Britannia, although both aircraft suffered protracted developments, with the latter entering service with BOAC in February 1957, over seven years following its order.
[src:escalator/airliner] The jet-powered Type IV became the de Havilland Comet in 1949.
[src:escalator/airliner] It featured an aerodynamically clean design with four de Havilland Ghost turbojet engines buried in the wings, a pressurised fuselage, and large square windows.
[src:escalator/airliner] On 2 May 1952, the Comet took off on the world's first jetliner flight carrying fare-paying passengers and simultaneously inaugurated scheduled service between London and Johannesburg.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, roughly one year after introduction, three Comets broke up mid-flight due to airframe metal fatigue, not well understood at the time.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Comet was grounded and tested to discover the cause, while rival manufacturers heeded the lessons learned while developing their own aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] The improved Comet 2 and the prototype Comet 3 culminated in the redesigned Comet 4 series which debuted in 1958 and had a productive career over 30 years, but sales never fully recovered.
[src:escalator/airliner] By the 1960s, the UK had lost the airliner market to the US due to the Comet disaster and a smaller domestic market, not regained by later designs like the BAC 1-11, Vickers VC10, and Hawker Siddeley Trident.
[src:escalator/airliner] The STAC committee was formed to consider supersonic designs and worked with Bristol to create the Bristol 223, a 100-passenger transatlantic airliner.
[src:escalator/airliner] The effort was later merged with similar efforts in France to create the Concorde supersonic airliner to share the cost.
[src:escalator/airliner] The first batch of the Douglas DC-4s went to the U.S.
[src:escalator/airliner] Army and Air Forces, and was named the C-54 Skymaster.
[src:escalator/airliner] Some ex-military DC-6s were later converted into airliners, with both passenger and cargo versions flooding the market shortly after the war's end.
[src:escalator/airliner] Douglas also developed a pressurized version of the DC-4, which it designated the Douglas DC-6.
[src:escalator/airliner] Rival company Lockheed produced the Constellation, a triple-tailed aircraft with a wider fuselage than the DC-4.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Boeing 377 Stratocruiser was based on the C-97 Stratofreighter military transport, it had a double deck and a pressurized fuselage.
[src:escalator/airliner] Convair produced the Convair 240, a 40-person pressurized airplane; 566 examples flew.
[src:escalator/airliner] Convair later developed the Convair 340, which was slightly larger and could accommodate between 44 and 52 passengers, of which 311 were produced.
[src:escalator/airliner] The firm also commenced work on the Convair 37, a relatively large double-deck airliner that would have served transcontinental routes; however, the project was abandoned due to a lack of customer demand and its high development costs.
[src:escalator/airliner] Rival planes include the Martin 2-0-2 and Martin 4-0-4, but the 2-0-2 had safety concerns and was unpressurized, while the 4-0-4 only sold around 100 units.
[src:escalator/airliner] During the postwar years, engines became much larger and more powerful, and safety features such as deicing, navigation, and weather information were added to the planes.
[src:escalator/airliner] American planes were allegedly more comfortable and had superior flight decks than those produced in Europe.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 1936, the French Air Ministry requested transatlantic flying boats that could hold at least 40 passengers, leading to three Latécoère 631s introduced by Air France in July 1947.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, two crashed and the third was removed from service over safety concerns.
[src:escalator/airliner] The SNCASE Languedoc was the first French post-war airliner.
[src:escalator/airliner] Accommodating up to 44 seats, 40 aircraft were completed for Air France between October 1945 and April 1948.
[src:escalator/airliner] Air France withdrew the last Languedoc from its domestic routes in 1954, being replaced by later designs.
[src:escalator/airliner] First flying in February 1949, the four-engined Breguet Deux-Ponts was a double-decker transport for passengers and cargo.
[src:escalator/airliner] Air France used it on its busiest routes, including from Paris to the Mediterranean area and to London.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Sud-Aviation Caravelle was developed during the late 1950s as the first short range jet airliner.
[src:escalator/airliner] The nose and cockpit layout were licensed from the de Havilland Comet, along with some fuselage elements.
[src:escalator/airliner] Entering service in mid 1959, 172 Caravelles had been sold within four years and six versions were in production by 1963.
[src:escalator/airliner] Sud Aviation then focused its design team on a Caravelle successor.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Super-Caravelle was a supersonic transport project of similar size and range to the Caravelle.
[src:escalator/airliner] It was merged with the similar Bristol Aeroplane Company project into the Anglo-French Concorde.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Concorde entered service in January 1967 as the second and last commercial supersonic transport, after large overruns and delays, costing £1.3 billion.
[src:escalator/airliner] All subsequent French airliner efforts were part of the Airbus pan-European initiative.
[src:escalator/airliner] Soon after the war, most of the Soviet fleet of airliners consisted of DC-3s or Lisunov Li-2s.
[src:escalator/airliner] These planes were in desperate need of replacement, and in 1946, the Ilyushin Il-12 made its first flight.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Il-12 was very similar in design to American Convair 240, except was unpressurized.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 1953, the Ilyushin Il-14 made its first flight, and this version was equipped with much more powerful engines.
[src:escalator/airliner] The main contribution that the Soviets made in regards to airliners was the Antonov An-2.
[src:escalator/airliner] This plane is a biplane, unlike most of the other airliners, and sold more units than any other transport plane.
[src:escalator/airliner] The most common airliners are the narrow-body aircraft, or single-aisles.
[src:escalator/airliner] The earliest jet airliners were narrowbodies: the initial de Havilland Comet, the Boeing 707 and its competitor the Douglas DC-8.
[src:escalator/airliner] They were followed by smaller models : the Douglas DC-9 and its MD-80/MD-90/Boeing 717 derivatives; the Boeing 727, 737 and 757 using the 707 cabin cross-section; or the Tupolev Tu-154, Ilyushin Il-18, and the Ilyushin Il-62.
[src:escalator/airliner] Currently produced narrow-body airliners include the Airbus A220, A320 family, Boeing 737, Embraer E-Jet family and Comac C919, generally used for medium-haul flights with 100 to 240 passengers.
[src:escalator/airliner] They could be joined by the in-development Irkut MC-21.
[src:escalator/airliner] The larger wide-body aircraft, or twin-aisle as they have two separate aisles in the cabin, are used for long-haul flights.
[src:escalator/airliner] The first was the Boeing 747 quadjet, followed by the trijets: the Lockheed L-1011 and the Douglas DC-10, then its MD-11 stretch.
[src:escalator/airliner] Then other quadjets were introduced: the Ilyushin Il-86 and Il-96, the Airbus A340 and the double-deck A380.
[src:escalator/airliner] Regional airliners seat fewer than 100 passengers.
[src:escalator/airliner] These smaller aircraft are often used to feed traffic at large airline hubs to larger aircraft operated by the major mainline carriers, legacy carriers, or flag carriers; often sharing the same livery.
[src:escalator/airliner] Regional jets include the Bombardier CRJ100/200 and Bombardier CRJ700 series, or the Embraer ERJ family.
[src:escalator/airliner] Currently produced turboprop regional airliners include the Dash-8 series, and the ATR 42/72.
[src:escalator/airliner] Light aircraft can be used as small commuter airliners, or as air taxis.
[src:escalator/airliner] Twin turboprops carrying up to 19 passengers include the Beechcraft 1900, Fairchild Metro, Jetstream 31, DHC-6 Twin Otter and Embraer EMB 110 Bandeirante.
[src:escalator/airliner] Smaller airliners include the single-engined turboprops like the Cessna Caravan and Pilatus PC-12; or twin piston-powered aircraft made by Cessna, Piper, Britten-Norman, and Beechcraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] They often lack lavatories, stand-up cabins, pressurization, galleys, overhead storage bins, reclining seats, or a flight attendant.
[src:escalator/airliner] Until the beginning of the Jet Age, piston engines were common on propliners such as the Douglas DC-3.
[src:escalator/airliner] Nearly all modern airliners are now powered by turbine engines, either turbofans or turboprops.
[src:escalator/airliner] Gas turbine engines operate efficiently at much higher altitudes, are more reliable than piston engines, and produce less vibration and noise.
[src:escalator/airliner] The use of a common fuel type – kerosene-based jet fuel – is another advantage.
[src:escalator/airliner] Some variants of airliners have been developed for carrying freight or for luxury corporate use.
[src:escalator/airliner] Modern jetliners are usually low-wing designs with two engines mounted underneath the swept wings, while turboprop aircraft are slow enough to use straight wings.
[src:escalator/airliner] Smaller airliners sometimes have their engines mounted on either side of the rear fuselage.
[src:escalator/airliner] Numerous advantages and disadvantages exist due to this arrangement.
[src:escalator/airliner] Perhaps the most important advantage to mounting the engines under the wings is that the total aircraft weight is more evenly distributed across the wingspan, which imposes less bending moment on the wings and allows for a lighter wing structure.
[src:escalator/airliner] This factor becomes more important as aircraft weight increases, and no in-production airliners have both a maximum takeoff weight more than 50 tons and engines mounted on the fuselage.
[src:escalator/airliner] The Antonov An-148 is the only in-production jetliner with high-mounted wings (usually seen in military transport aircraft), which reduces the risk of damage from unpaved runways.
[src:escalator/airliner] Except for a few experimental or military designs, all aircraft built to date have had all of their weight lifted off the ground by airflow across the wings.
[src:escalator/airliner] In terms of aerodynamics, the fuselage has been a mere burden.
[src:escalator/airliner] NASA and Boeing are currently developing a blended wing body design in which the entire airframe, from wingtip to wingtip, contributes lift.
[src:escalator/airliner] This promises a significant gain in fuel efficiency.
[src:escalator/airliner] The narrow-body and wide-body airliner market is dominated by Airbus and Boeing, and the regional airliner market is shared between ATR Aircraft, De Havilland Canada, and Embraer.
[src:escalator/airliner] Setting up a reliable customer support network, ensuring uptime, availability and support 24/7 and anywhere, is critical for the success of airliner manufacturers.
[src:escalator/airliner] Boeing and Airbus are ranked 1 and 2 in customer satisfaction for aftermarket support by a survey by Inside MRO and Air Transport World, and this is a reason why Mitsubishi Aircraft Corporation purchased the Bombardier CRJ program.
[src:escalator/airliner] It is an entry barrier for new entrants like the Xian MA700 and Comac C919, with no credible previous experience with the MA60, or the Irkut MC-21 after the Sukhoi Superjet 100.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 2018, there were 29,398 airliners in service: 26,935 passenger transports and 2,463 freighters, while 2,754 others were stored.
[src:escalator/airliner] The largest fleet was in Asia-Pacific with 8,808 (5% stored), followed by 8,572 in North America (10% stored), 7,254 in Europe (9% stored), 2,027 in Latin America, 1,510 in Middle East and 1,347 in Africa.
[src:escalator/airliner] Narrowbody are dominant with 16,235, followed by 5,581 Widebodies, 3,743 Turboprops, 3,565 Regional jets and 399 Others.
[src:escalator/airliner] By the end of 2018, there were 1,826 parked or in storage jetliners out of 29,824 in service (6.1%): 1,434 narrowbodies and 392 widebodies, down from 9.8% of the fleet at the end of 2012 and 11.3% at the end of 2001.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 2004, 718 Airbus and Boeings were delivered, worth $39.3 billion; 1,466 are expected in 2017, worth $104.4 billion: a growth by 3.5 from 2004 to 2020 is unprecedented and highly unusual for any mature market.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 2016, the deliveries went for 38% in Asia-Pacific, 25% in Europe, 22% in North America, 7% in Middle East, 6% in South America and 2% in Africa.
[src:escalator/airliner] The most important driver of orders is airline profitability, itself driven mainly by world GDP growth but also supply and demand balance and oil prices, while new programmes by Airbus and Boeing help to stimulate aircraft demand.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 2016, 38% of the 25 years old airliners had been retired, 50% of the 28 years old : there will be 523 aircraft reaching 25 years old in 2017, 1,127 in 2026 and 1,628 in 2041.
[src:escalator/airliner] Deliveries rose by 80% from 2004 to 2016, they represented 4.9% of the fleet in 2004 and 5.9% in 2016, down from 8% previously.
[src:escalator/airliner] Oil prices and airshow orders are trending together.
[src:escalator/airliner] In 2020, deliveries were down by more than 50% compared to 2019 due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation, after 10 years of growth.
[src:escalator/airliner] Storage can be an adjustment variable for the airliner fleet: as Jan–Apr 2018 RPKs are up by 7% over a year and FTKs up by 5.1%, the IATA reports 81 net aircraft went back from storage (132 recalled and 51 stored) in April.
[src:escalator/airliner] It is the second month of storage contraction after eight of expansion and the largest in four years, while new aircraft deliveries fell slightly to 448 from 454 due to supply-chain issues and in-service issues grounding others.
[src:escalator/airliner] Retirements were down by 8% and utilization up by 2%, according to Canaccord Genuity, driving used aircraft and engines values up while MRO shops have unexpected demand for legacy products like the PW4000 and GE CF6.
[src:escalator/airliner] An airliner will usually have several classes of seating: first class, business class, and/or economy class (which may be referred to as coach class or tourist class, and sometimes has a separate "premium" economy section with more legroom and amenities).
[src:escalator/airliner] The seats in more expensive classes are wider, more comfortable, and have more amenities such as "lie flat" seats for more comfortable sleeping on long flights.
[src:escalator/airliner] Generally, the more expensive the class, the better the beverage and meal service.
[src:escalator/airliner] Domestic flights generally have a two-class configuration, usually first or business class and coach class, although many airlines instead offer all-economy seating.
[src:escalator/airliner] International flights generally have either a two-class configuration or a three-class configuration, depending on the airline, route and aircraft type.
[src:escalator/airliner] Many airliners offer movies or audio/video on demand (this is standard in first and business class on many international flights and may be available on economy).
[src:escalator/airliner] Cabins of all classes have lavatory facilities, reading lights, and air vents.
[src:escalator/airliner] Some larger airliners have a rest compartment reserved for crew use during breaks.
[src:escalator/airliner] The types of seats that are provided and how much legroom is given to each passenger are decisions made by the individual airlines, not the aircraft manufacturers.
[src:escalator/airliner] Seats are mounted in "tracks" on the floor of the cabin and can be moved back and forth by the maintenance staff or removed altogether.
[src:escalator/airliner] One driver of airline profitability is how many passengers can be seated in economy class cabins, meaning that airline companies have an incentive to place seats close together to fit as many passengers in as possible.
[src:escalator/airliner] In contrast, ‘premium class’ seat configurations provide more space for travelers.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, passengers seated in an exit row may be required to assist cabin crew during an emergency evacuation of the aircraft opening the emergency exit and assisting fellow passengers to the exit.
[src:escalator/airliner] As a precaution, many airlines prohibit young people under the age of 15 from being seated in the exit row.
[src:escalator/airliner] The seats are designed to withstand strong forces so as not to break or come loose from their floor tracks during turbulence or accidents.
[src:escalator/airliner] The backs of seats are often equipped with a fold-down tray for eating, writing, or as a place to set up a portable computer, or a music or video player.
[src:escalator/airliner] Seats without another row of seats in front of them have a tray that is either folded into the armrest or that clips into brackets on the underside of the armrests.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, seats in premium cabins generally have trays in the armrests or clip-on trays, regardless of whether there is another row of seats in front of them.
[src:escalator/airliner] Seatbacks now often feature small colour LCD screens for videos, television and video games.
[src:escalator/airliner] Controls for this display as well as an outlet to plug in audio headsets are normally found in the armrest of each seat.
[src:escalator/airliner] The overhead bins, also known as overhead lockers or pivot bins, are used for stowing carry-on baggage and other items.
[src:escalator/airliner] While the airliner manufacturer will normally specify a standard version of the product to supply, airlines can choose to have bins of differing size, shape, or color installed.
[src:escalator/airliner] Over time, overhead bins evolved out of what were originally overhead shelves that were used for little more than coat and briefcase storage.
[src:escalator/airliner] As concerns about falling debris during turbulence or in accidents increased, enclosed bins became the norm.
[src:escalator/airliner] Bins have increased in size to accommodate the larger carry-on baggage passengers can bring onto the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] Newer bin designs have included a handrail, useful when moving through the cabin.
[src:escalator/airliner] Above the passenger seats are Passenger Service Units (PSU).
[src:escalator/airliner] These typically contain reading lights, air vents, and a flight attendant call light.
[src:escalator/airliner] The units frequently have small "Fasten Seat Belt" and "No Smoking" illuminated signage and may also contain a speaker for the cabin public address system.
[src:escalator/airliner] On some newer aircraft, a "Turn off electronic devices" sign is used instead of the "No Smoking" sign, as smoking isn't permitted on board the aircraft anyway.
[src:escalator/airliner] The PSU will also normally contain the drop-down oxygen masks which are activated if there is a sudden drop in cabin pressure.
[src:escalator/airliner] These are supplied with oxygen by means of a chemical oxygen generator.
[src:escalator/airliner] By using a chemical reaction rather than a connection to an oxygen tank, these devices supply breathing oxygen for long enough for the airliner to descend to thicker, more breathable air.
[src:escalator/airliner] Oxygen generators do generate considerable heat in the process.
[src:escalator/airliner] Because of this, the oxygen generators are thermally shielded and are only allowed in commercial airliners when properly installed – they are not permitted to be loaded as freight on passenger-carrying flights.
[src:escalator/airliner] ValuJet Flight 592 crashed on May 11, 1996, as a result of improperly loaded chemical oxygen generators.
[src:escalator/airliner] Airliners developed since the 1940s have had pressurized cabins (or, more accurately, pressurized hulls including baggage holds) to enable them to carry passengers safely at high altitudes where low oxygen levels and air pressure would otherwise cause sickness or death.
[src:escalator/airliner] High altitude flight enabled airliners to fly above most weather systems that cause turbulent or dangerous flying conditions, and also to fly faster and further as there is less drag due to the lower air density.
[src:escalator/airliner] Pressurization is applied using compressed air, in most cases bled from the engines, and is managed by an environmental control system which draws in clean air, and vents stale air out through a valve.
[src:escalator/airliner] Pressurization presents design and construction challenges to maintain the structural integrity and sealing of the cabin and hull and to prevent rapid decompression.
[src:escalator/airliner] Some of the consequences include small round windows, doors that open inwards and are larger than the door hole, and an emergency oxygen system.
[src:escalator/airliner] To maintain a pressure in the cabin equivalent to an altitude close to sea level would, at a cruising altitude around 10,000 m (33,000 ft), create a pressure difference between inside the aircraft and outside the aircraft that would require greater hull strength and weight.
[src:escalator/airliner] Most people do not suffer ill effects up to an altitude of 1,800–2,500 m (5,900–8,200 ft), and maintaining cabin pressure at this equivalent altitude significantly reduces the pressure difference and therefore the required hull strength and weight.
[src:escalator/airliner] A side effect is that passengers experience some discomfort as the cabin pressure changes during ascent and descent to the majority of airports, which are at low altitudes.
[src:escalator/airliner] The air bled from the engines is hot and requires cooling by air conditioning units.
[src:escalator/airliner] It is also extremely dry at cruising altitude, and this causes sore eyes, dry skin and mucosa on long flights.
[src:escalator/airliner] Another problem of the air coming from the ventilation (unto which the oil lubrication system of the engines is hooked up) is that fumes from components in the synthetic oils can sometimes travel along, causing passengers, pilots and crew to be intoxicated.
[src:escalator/airliner] The illness it causes is called aerotoxic syndrome.
[src:escalator/airliner] Airliners must have space on board to store "checked" baggage – that which will not safely fit in the passenger cabin.
[src:escalator/airliner] Designed to hold baggage as well as freight, these compartments are called "cargo bins", "baggage holds", "luggage holds", or occasionally "pits".
[src:escalator/airliner] Occasionally baggage holds may be referred to as **cargo decks** on the largest of aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] These compartments can be accessed through doors on the outside of the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] Depending on the aircraft, baggage holds are normally inside the hull and are therefore pressurized just like the passenger cabin although they may not be heated.
[src:escalator/airliner] While lighting is normally installed for use by the loading crew, typically the compartment is unlit when the door is closed.
[src:escalator/airliner] Baggage holds on modern airliners are equipped with fire detection equipment and larger aircraft have automated or remotely activated fire-fighting devices installed.
[src:escalator/airliner] Most "narrow-body" airliners with more than 100 seats have space below the cabin floor, while smaller aircraft often have a special compartment separate from the passenger area but on the same level.
[src:escalator/airliner] Baggage is normally stacked within the bin by hand, sorted by destination category.
[src:escalator/airliner] Netting that fits across the width of the bin is secured to limit movement of the bags.
[src:escalator/airliner] Airliners often carry items of freight and mail.
[src:escalator/airliner] These may be loaded separately from the baggage or mixed in if they are bound for the same destination.
[src:escalator/airliner] For securing bulky items "hold down" rings are provided to tie items into place.
[src:escalator/airliner] "Wide-body" airliners frequently have a compartment like the ones described above, typically called a "bulk bin".
[src:escalator/airliner] It is normally used for late arriving luggage or bags which may have been checked at the gate.
[src:escalator/airliner] However, most baggage and loose freight items are loaded into containers called Unit Load Devices (ULDs), often referred to as "cans".
[src:escalator/airliner] ULDs come in a variety of sizes and shapes, but the most common model is the LD3.
[src:escalator/airliner] This particular container has approximately the same height as the cargo compartment and fits across half of its width.
[src:escalator/airliner] ULDs are loaded with baggage and are transported to the aircraft on dolly carts and loaded into the baggage hold by a loader designed for the task.
[src:escalator/airliner] By means of belts and rollers an operator can maneuver the ULD from the dolly cart, up to the aircraft baggage hold door, and into the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airliner] Inside the hold, the floor is also equipped with drive wheels and rollers that an operator inside can use to move the ULD properly into place.
[src:escalator/airliner] Locks in the floor are used to hold the ULD in place during flight.
[src:escalator/airliner] For consolidated freight loads, like a pallet of boxes or an item too oddly shaped to fit into a container, flat metal pallets that resemble large baking sheets that are compatible with the loading equipment are used.
[src:escalator/airport] An **airport** is an aerodrome with extended facilities, mostly for commercial air transport.
[src:escalator/airport] Larger airports may have airport aprons, taxiway bridges, air traffic control centres, passenger facilities such as restaurants and lounges, and emergency services.
[src:escalator/airport] In some countries, the US in particular, airports also typically have one or more fixed-base operators, serving general aviation.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport operations are extremely complex, with a complicated system of aircraft support services, passenger services, and aircraft control services contained within the operation.
[src:escalator/airport] Thus airports can be major employers, as well as important hubs for tourism and other kinds of transit.
[src:escalator/airport] Because they are sites of operation for heavy machinery, a number of regulations and safety measures have been implemented in airports, in order to reduce hazards.
[src:escalator/airport] Additionally, airports have major local environmental impacts, as both large sources of air pollution, noise pollution and other environmental impacts, making them sites that acutely experience the environmental effects of aviation.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports are also vulnerable infrastructure to extreme weather, climate change caused sea level rise and other disasters.
[src:escalator/airport] The terms *aerodrome*, *airfield*, and *airstrip* also refer to airports, and the terms *heliport*, *seaplane base*, and *STOLport* refer to airports dedicated exclusively to helicopters, seaplanes, and short take-off and landing aircraft, respectively.
[src:escalator/airport] The word aeroplane emerged in the 1870s, long before the Wright brothers succeeded in 1903.
[src:escalator/airport] In colloquial use in certain environments, the terms *airport* and *aerodrome* are often interchanged.
[src:escalator/airport] However, in general, the term *airport* may imply or confer a certain stature upon the aviation facility that other aerodromes may not have achieved.
[src:escalator/airport] In some jurisdictions, *airport* is a legal term of art reserved exclusively for those aerodromes certified or licensed as airports by the relevant civil aviation authority after meeting specified certification criteria or regulatory requirements.
[src:escalator/airport] That is to say, all airports are aerodromes, but not all aerodromes are airports.
[src:escalator/airport] In jurisdictions where there is no legal distinction between *aerodrome* and *airport*, which term to use in the name of an aerodrome may be a commercial decision.
[src:escalator/airport] In US technical/legal usage, *landing area* is used instead of *aerodrome*, and *airport* means "a landing area used regularly by aircraft for receiving or discharging passengers or cargo".
[src:escalator/airport] Smaller or less-developed airfields, which represent the vast majority, often have a single runway shorter than 1,000 m (3,300 ft).
[src:escalator/airport] Larger airports for airline flights generally have paved runways of 2,000 m (6,600 ft) or longer.
[src:escalator/airport] Skyline Airport in Inkom, Idaho, has a runway that is only 122 m (400 ft) long.
[src:escalator/airport] As of 2009, the CIA stated that there were approximately 44,000 "airports or airfields recognizable from the air" around the world, including 15,095 in the US, the US having the most in the world.
[src:escalator/airport] Many US airports still lease part or all of their facilities to outside firms, who operate functions such as retail management and parking.
[src:escalator/airport] All US commercial airport runways are certified by the FAA under the Code of Federal Regulations Title 14 Part 139, "Certification of Commercial Service Airports".
[src:escalator/airport] The Airport & Airway Trust Fund (AATF) was created by the Airport and Airway Development in 1970 which finances aviation programs in the United States.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport Improvement Program (AIP), Facilities and Equipment (F&E), and Research, Engineering, and Development (RE&D) are the three major accounts of Federal Aviation Administration which are financed by the AATF, as well as pays for the FAA's Operation and Maintenance (O&M) account.
[src:escalator/airport] The funding of these accounts are dependent on the taxes the airports generate of revenues.
[src:escalator/airport] Passenger tickets, fuel, and cargo tax are the taxes that are paid by the passengers and airlines help fund these accounts.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports revenues are divided into three major parts: aeronautical revenue, non-aeronautical revenue, and non-operating revenue.
[src:escalator/airport] Aeronautical revenue makes up 50% in 2021 (from 54% and 48% in 2019 and 2020, non-aeronautical revenue makes up 34% (40%, 39% in previous years), and non-operating revenue makes up 16% (6%, 14%) of the total revenue of airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Aeronautical revenue are generated through airline rents and landing, passenger service, parking, and hangar fees.
[src:escalator/airport] Landing fees are charged per aircraft for landing an airplane in the airport property.
[src:escalator/airport] Landing fees are calculated through the landing weight and the size of the aircraft which varies but most of the airports have a fixed rate and charge extra for extra weight.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft parking is also a major revenue source for airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft are parked for a certain amount of time before or after takeoff and have to pay to park there.
[src:escalator/airport] Every airport has its own rates of parking, for example, John F.
[src:escalator/airport] Kennedy International Airport in New York City charges $45 per hour for a plane of 100,000 pounds and the price increases with weight.
[src:escalator/airport] Non-aeronautical revenue is gained through things other than aircraft operations.
[src:escalator/airport] It includes lease revenue from compatible land-use development, non-aeronautical building leases, retail and concession sales, rental car operations, parking and in-airport advertising.
[src:escalator/airport] Concession revenue is one big part of non-aeronautical revenue airports make through duty free, bookstores, restaurants and money exchange.
[src:escalator/airport] Car parking is a growing source of revenue for airports, as more people use the parking facilities of the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] O'Hare International Airport in Chicago charges $2 per hour for every car.
[src:escalator/airport] To prevent them from abusing their market power, governments regulate how much airports may charge to airlines, using price-cap regulation.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports are divided into landside and airside zones.
[src:escalator/airport] The landside is subject to fewer special laws and is part of the public realm, while access to the airside zone is tightly controlled; only passengers with a valid boarding pass, aircrew members with an identification document, and airport staff with a valid airside pass can access the airside.
[src:escalator/airport] Landside facilities may include publicly accessible airport check-in desks, shops and ground transportation facilities.
[src:escalator/airport] The area where the aircraft parks to load passengers and baggage is known as an *apron* or *ramp* (or incorrectly, "the tarmac").
[src:escalator/airport] Airport security normally requires baggage checks, metal screenings of individual persons, and rules against any object that could be used as a weapon.
[src:escalator/airport] It uses technology such as x-rays and metal detectors.
[src:escalator/airport] Since the September 11 attacks and the Real ID Act of 2005, airport security has dramatically increased and gotten tighter and stricter than ever before.
[src:escalator/airport] Most major airports provide commercial outlets for products and services.
[src:escalator/airport] Most of these companies, many of which are internationally known brands, are located within the departure areas.
[src:escalator/airport] These include clothing boutiques and restaurants and in the US amounted to $4.2 billion in 2015.
[src:escalator/airport] Prices charged for items sold at these outlets are generally higher than those outside the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] However, some airports now regulate costs to keep them comparable to "street prices".
[src:escalator/airport] This term is misleading as prices often match the manufacturers' suggested retail price (MSRP) but are almost never discounted.
[src:escalator/airport] Many new airports include walkthrough duty-free stores that require air passengers to enter a retail store upon exiting security.
[src:escalator/airport] Apart from major fast food chains, some airport restaurants offer regional cuisine specialties for those in transit so that they may sample local food without leaving the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports may also contain premium and VIP services.
[src:escalator/airport] The premium and VIP services may include express check-in and dedicated check-in counters.
[src:escalator/airport] These services are usually reserved for first and business class passengers, premium frequent flyers, and members of the airline's clubs.
[src:escalator/airport] Premium services may sometimes be open to passengers who are members of a different airline's frequent flyer program.
[src:escalator/airport] This can sometimes be part of a reciprocal deal, as when multiple airlines are part of the same alliance, or as a ploy to attract premium customers away from rival airlines.
[src:escalator/airport] Sometimes these premium services will be offered to a non-premium passenger if the airline has made a mistake in handling of the passenger, such as unreasonable delays or mishandling of checked baggage.
[src:escalator/airport] Airline lounges frequently offer free or reduced cost food, as well as alcoholic and non-alcoholic beverages.
[src:escalator/airport] Lounges themselves typically have seating, showers, quiet areas, televisions, computer, Wi-Fi and Internet access, and power outlets that passengers may use for their electronic equipment.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airline lounges employ baristas, bartenders and gourmet chefs.
[src:escalator/airport] Airlines sometimes operate multiple lounges within the one airport terminal allowing ultra-premium customers, such as first class customers, additional services, which are not available to other premium customers.
[src:escalator/airport] Multiple lounges may also prevent overcrowding of the lounge facilities.
[src:escalator/airport] In addition to people, airports move cargo around the clock.
[src:escalator/airport] Cargo airlines often have their own on-site and adjacent infrastructure to transfer parcels between ground and air.
[src:escalator/airport] Cargo Terminal Facilities are areas where international airports export cargo has to be stored after customs clearance and prior to loading the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] Similarly, import cargo that is offloaded needs to be in bond before the consignee decides to take delivery.
[src:escalator/airport] Areas have to be kept aside for examination of export and import cargo by the airport authorities.
[src:escalator/airport] Designated areas or sheds may be given to airlines or freight forward ring agencies.
[src:escalator/airport] Every cargo terminal has a landside and an airside.
[src:escalator/airport] The landside is where the exporters and importers through either their agents or by themselves deliver or collect shipments while the airside is where loads are moved to or from the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] In addition, cargo terminals are divided into distinct areas – export, import, and interline or transshipment.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports require parking lots, for passengers who may leave the cars at the airport for a long period of time.
[src:escalator/airport] Large airports will also have car-rental firms, taxi ranks, bus stops and sometimes a train station.
[src:escalator/airport] It is also common to connect an airport and a city with rapid transit, light rail lines or other non-road public transport systems.
[src:escalator/airport] Some examples of this would include the AirTrain JFK at John F.
[src:escalator/airport] Kennedy International Airport in New York, Link light rail that runs from the heart of downtown Seattle to Seattle–Tacoma International Airport, and the Silver Line T at Boston's Logan International Airport by the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA).
[src:escalator/airport] Such a connection lowers risk of missed flights due to traffic congestion.
[src:escalator/airport] Large airports usually have access also through controlled-access highways ('freeways' or 'motorways') from which motor vehicles enter either the departure loop or the arrival loop.
[src:escalator/airport] The distances passengers need to move within a large airport can be substantial.
[src:escalator/airport] It is common for airports to provide moving walkways, buses, and rail transport systems.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airports like Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport and London Stansted Airport have a transit system that connects some of the gates to a main terminal.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports with more than one terminal have a transit system to connect the terminals together, such as John F.
[src:escalator/airport] Kennedy International Airport, Mexico City International Airport and London Gatwick Airport.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport operations are made possible by an organized network of trained personnel, specialized equipment, and spatial data.
[src:escalator/airport] Air traffic controllers on the ground help direct aircraft through a region of airspace, communicating with aircraft to coordinate their paths.
[src:escalator/airport] Their tasks include maintaining a safe distance between aircraft, avoiding congestion, and rerouting aircraft to deal with adverse weather.
[src:escalator/airport] Most air traffic control centers can be divided into terminal control centers, which control the small, highly used region around an airport, and area control centers, which control aircraft *en route* to their destinations in a larger area.
[src:escalator/airport] Both terminal and area control centers use radio to communicate with pilots and radar to track their paths, and in terminal control centers visual observation can also be used, as most aircraft near a terminal control center are either taking off or landing.
[src:escalator/airport] Ground control is responsible for directing all ground traffic in designated "movement areas", except the traffic on runways.
[src:escalator/airport] This includes planes, baggage trains, snowplows, grass cutters, fuel trucks, stair trucks, airline food trucks, conveyor belt vehicles and other vehicles.
[src:escalator/airport] Ground Control will instruct these vehicles on which taxiways to use, which runway they will use (in the case of planes), where they will park, and when it is safe to cross runways.
[src:escalator/airport] When a plane is ready to takeoff it will be turned over to tower control.
[src:escalator/airport] Conversely, after a plane has landed it will depart the runway and be "handed over" from Tower to Ground Control.
[src:escalator/airport] Tower control is responsible for aircraft on the runway and in the controlled airspace immediately surrounding the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] Tower controllers may use radar to locate an aircraft's position in 3D space, or they may rely on pilot position reports and visual observation.
[src:escalator/airport] They coordinate the sequencing of aircraft in the traffic pattern and direct aircraft on how to safely join and leave the circuit.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft which are only passing through the airspace must also contact tower control to be sure they remain clear of other traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] At all airports the use of a traffic pattern (often called a *traffic circuit* outside the US) is possible.
[src:escalator/airport] They may help to assure smooth traffic flow between departing and arriving aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] There is no technical need within modern commercial aviation for performing this pattern, *provided there is no queue*.
[src:escalator/airport] And due to the so-called SLOT-times, the overall traffic planning tend to assure landing queues are avoided.
[src:escalator/airport] If for instance an aircraft approaches runway 17 (which has a heading of approx.
[src:escalator/airport] 170 degrees) from the north (coming from 360/0 degrees heading towards 180 degrees), the aircraft will land as fast as possible by just turning 10 degrees and follow the glidepath, without orbit the runway for visual reasons, whenever this is possible.
[src:escalator/airport] For smaller piston engined airplanes at smaller airfields without ILS equipment, things are very different though.
[src:escalator/airport] Generally, this pattern is a circuit consisting of five "legs" that form a rectangle (two legs and the runway form one side, with the remaining legs forming three more sides).
[src:escalator/airport] Each leg is named (see diagram), and ATC directs pilots on how to join and leave the circuit.
[src:escalator/airport] Traffic patterns are flown at one specific altitude, usually 800 or 1,000 ft (244 or 305 m) above ground level (AGL).
[src:escalator/airport] Standard traffic patterns are *left-handed*, meaning all turns are made to the left.
[src:escalator/airport] One of the main reason for this is that pilots sit on the left side of the airplane, and a Left-hand patterns improves their visibility of the airport and pattern.
[src:escalator/airport] Right-handed patterns do exist, usually because of obstacles such as a mountain, or to reduce noise for local residents.
[src:escalator/airport] The predetermined circuit helps traffic flow smoothly because all pilots know what to expect, and helps reduce the chance of a mid-air collision.
[src:escalator/airport] At controlled airports, a circuit can be in place but is not normally used.
[src:escalator/airport] Rather, aircraft (usually only commercial with long routes) request approach clearance while they are still hours away from the airport; the destination airport can then plan a queue of arrivals, and planes will be guided into one queue per active runway for a "straight-in" approach.
[src:escalator/airport] While this system keeps the airspace free and is simpler for pilots, it requires detailed knowledge of how aircraft are planning to use the airport ahead of time and is therefore only possible with large commercial airliners on pre-scheduled flights.
[src:escalator/airport] The system has recently become so advanced that controllers can predict whether an aircraft will be delayed on landing before it even takes off; that aircraft can then be delayed on the ground, rather than wasting expensive fuel waiting in the air.
[src:escalator/airport] There are a number of aids, both visual and electronic, though not at all airports.
[src:escalator/airport] A visual approach slope indicator (VASI) helps pilots fly the approach for landing.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airports are equipped with a VHF omnidirectional range (VOR) to help pilots find the direction to the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] VORs are often accompanied by a distance measuring equipment (DME) to determine the distance to the VOR.
[src:escalator/airport] VORs are also located off airports, where they serve to provide airways for aircraft to navigate upon.
[src:escalator/airport] In poor weather, pilots will use an instrument landing system (ILS) to find the runway and fly the correct approach, even if they cannot see the ground.
[src:escalator/airport] The number of instrument approaches based on the use of the Global Positioning System (GPS) is rapidly increasing and may eventually become the primary means for instrument landings.
[src:escalator/airport] Larger airports sometimes offer precision approach radar (PAR), but these systems are more common at military air bases than civilian airports.
[src:escalator/airport] The aircraft's horizontal and vertical movement is tracked via radar, and the controller tells the pilot his position relative to the approach slope.
[src:escalator/airport] Once the pilots can see the runway lights, they may continue with a visual landing.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport guidance signs provide direction and information to taxiing aircraft and airport vehicles.
[src:escalator/airport] Smaller aerodromes may have few or no signs, relying instead on diagrams and charts.
[src:escalator/airport] Taxiway lights use color codes to mark out different sections of the taxiway.
[src:escalator/airport] Blue lights normally indicate the edge of the taxiway, and green lights are located in its center.
[src:escalator/airport] Red lights are placed where the runway begins, and are turned off once the pilot has gained clearance from the air traffic control to take off.
[src:escalator/airport] Weather observations at the airport are crucial to safe takeoffs and landings.
[src:escalator/airport] In the United States and Canada, the vast majority of airports, large and small, will either have some form of automated airport weather station, whether an AWOS, ASOS, or AWSS, a human observer or a combination of the two.
[src:escalator/airport] These weather observations, predominantly in the METAR format, are available over the radio, through automatic terminal information service (ATIS), via the ATC or the flight service station.
[src:escalator/airport] Planes take-off and land *into* the wind to achieve maximum performance.
[src:escalator/airport] Because pilots need instantaneous information during landing, a windsock can also be kept in view of the runway.
[src:escalator/airport] Aviation windsocks are made with lightweight material, withstand strong winds and some are lit up after dark or in foggy weather.
[src:escalator/airport] Because visibility of windsocks is limited, often multiple glow-orange windsocks are placed on both sides of the runway.
[src:escalator/airport] Each airport hires its own ground crew to process flights, cargo, passengers, and baggage.
[src:escalator/airport] When a flight arrives, ramp services navigate a baggage cart to the aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] Bags are then sorted and transported by baggage handlers.
[src:escalator/airport] Ramp services handle aircraft marshaling, the process in which aircraft arrive or depart from the gate.
[src:escalator/airport] Once passengers and/or cargo is unloaded, a cleaning crew prepares the aircraft for its next flight by loading supplies and preparing other in-flight services.
[src:escalator/airport] Ground crew will fuel the aircraft, and other visual inspections are conducted.
[src:escalator/airport] Efficient work allows aircraft to have fast turnaround times of as little as 25 minutes.
[src:escalator/airport] Like industrial equipment or facility management, airports require tailor-made maintenance management due to their complexity.
[src:escalator/airport] With many tangible assets spread over a large area in different environments, these infrastructures must therefore effectively monitor these assets and store spare parts to maintain them at an optimal level of service.
[src:escalator/airport] To manage these airport assets, several solutions are competing for the market: CMMS (computerized maintenance management system) predominate, and mainly enable a company's maintenance activity to be monitored, planned, recorded and rationalized.
[src:escalator/airport] Aviation safety is an important concern in the operation of an airport, and almost every airfield includes equipment and procedures for handling emergency situations.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport crash tender crews are equipped for dealing with airfield accidents, crew and passenger extractions, and the hazards of highly flammable aviation fuel.
[src:escalator/airport] The crews are also trained to deal with situations such as bomb threats, hijacking, and terrorist activities.
[src:escalator/airport] Hazards to aircraft include debris, nesting birds, and reduced friction levels due to environmental conditions such as ice, snow, or rain.
[src:escalator/airport] Part of runway maintenance is airfield rubber removal which helps maintain friction levels.
[src:escalator/airport] The fields must be kept clear of debris using cleaning equipment so that loose material does not become a projectile and enter an engine duct (see foreign object damage).
[src:escalator/airport] In adverse weather conditions, ice and snow clearing equipment can be used to improve traction on the landing strip.
[src:escalator/airport] For waiting aircraft, equipment is used to spray special deicing fluids on the wings.
[src:escalator/airport] Many airports are built near open fields or wetlands.
[src:escalator/airport] These tend to attract bird populations, which can pose a hazard to aircraft in the form of bird strikes.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport crews often need to discourage birds from taking up residence.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airports are located next to parks, golf courses, or other low-density uses of land.
[src:escalator/airport] Other airports are located near densely populated urban or suburban areas.
[src:escalator/airport] An airport can have areas where collisions between aircraft on the ground tend to occur.
[src:escalator/airport] Records are kept of any incursions where aircraft or vehicles are in an inappropriate location, allowing these "hot spots" to be identified.
[src:escalator/airport] These locations then undergo special attention by transportation authorities (such as the FAA in the US) and airport administrators.
[src:escalator/airport] During the 1980s, a phenomenon known as microburst became a growing concern due to aircraft accidents caused by microburst wind shear, such as Delta Air Lines Flight 191.
[src:escalator/airport] Microburst radar was developed as an aid to safety during landing, giving two to five minutes' warning to aircraft in the vicinity of the field of a microburst event.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airfields now have a special surface known as soft concrete at the end of the runway (stopway or blastpad) that behaves somewhat like styrofoam, bringing the plane to a relatively rapid halt as the material disintegrates.
[src:escalator/airport] These surfaces are useful when the runway is located next to a body of water or other hazard, and prevent the planes from overrunning the end of the field.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports often have on-site firefighters to respond to emergencies.
[src:escalator/airport] These use specialized vehicles, known as airport crash tenders.
[src:escalator/airport] Most civil aviation authorities have required levels of on-site emergency response capabilities based on an airport's traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] At airports where civil and military operations share a common set of runways and infrastructure, emergency response is often managed by the relevant military unit as part of their base's operations.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft noise is a major cause of noise disturbance to residents living near airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Sleep can be affected if the airports operate night and early morning flights.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft noise occurs not only from take-offs and landings but also from ground operations including maintenance and testing of aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] Noise can have other health effects as well.
[src:escalator/airport] Other noises and environmental concerns are vehicle traffic causing noise and pollution on roads leading to the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] The construction of new airports or addition of runways to existing airports, is often resisted by local residents because of the effect on countryside, historical sites, and local flora and fauna.
[src:escalator/airport] Due to the risk of collision between birds and aircraft, large airports undertake population control programs where they frighten or shoot birds.
[src:escalator/airport] The construction of airports has been known to change local weather patterns.
[src:escalator/airport] For example, because they often flatten out large areas, they can be susceptible to fog in areas where fog rarely forms.
[src:escalator/airport] In addition, they generally replace trees and grass with pavement, they often change drainage patterns in agricultural areas, leading to more flooding, run-off and erosion in the surrounding land.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports are often built on low-lying coastal land, globally 269 airports are at risk of coastal flooding now.
[src:escalator/airport] A temperature rise of 2 °C – consistent with the Paris Agreement – would lead to 100 airports being below mean sea level and 364 airports at risk of flooding.
[src:escalator/airport] If global mean temperature rise exceeds this then as many as 572 airports will be at risk by 2100, leading to major disruptions without appropriate adaptation.
[src:escalator/airport] A 2019 report from the Cooperative Research Programs of the US Transportation Research Board showed all airports have a role to play in advancing greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction initiatives.
[src:escalator/airport] Small airports have demonstrated leadership by using their less complex organizational structure to implement newer technologies and to serve as a proving ground for their feasibility.
[src:escalator/airport] Large airports have the economic stability and staff resources necessary to grow in-house expertise and fund comprehensive new programs.
[src:escalator/airport] A growing number of airports are installing solar photovoltaic arrays to offset their electricity use.
[src:escalator/airport] The National Renewable Energy Lab has shown this can be done safely.
[src:escalator/airport] This can also be done on the roofs of the airports and it has been found that the solar panels on these buildings work more effectively when compared to residential panels.
[src:escalator/airport] The world's first airport to be fully powered by solar energy is located at Kochi, India.
[src:escalator/airport] As a part of their sustainability efforts, more and more airports are starting to explore the consequences of more electric aircraft coming into service.
[src:escalator/airport] Electric aircraft require much energy; operating 49 small 50-passenger short-range battery electric aircraft would demand at least 16 GWh/year, and with short turnaround times between different flights, the charging powers have to be substantial.
[src:escalator/airport] To tackle these issues, more airports are starting to look into alternative energy production such as solar power and wind power, but also how to use airport areas for biomass production.
[src:escalator/airport] Another solution investigated is to use energy storage to charge during the night and use to charge the aircraft during daytime.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports, as major international travel hubs, have the potential to be significant transmission points for infectious diseases.
[src:escalator/airport] A notable study conducted during the peak of the 2015–2016 flu season at Helsinki-Vantaa airport in Finland revealed that commonly touched surfaces in airports, especially the plastic security screening trays, are highly susceptible to contamination by respiratory viruses.
[src:escalator/airport] These trays are touched by hundreds of passengers daily and, being made of plastic, a non-porous material, provide an environment where viruses can survive for extended periods.
[src:escalator/airport] In comparison, bathroom surfaces in the same airport tested negative for respiratory viruses, possibly indicating a heightened awareness of hygiene in these spaces.
[src:escalator/airport] Hand hygiene plays a pivotal role in preventing the spread of infectious diseases in airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Research indicates that only about 70% of individuals wash their hands after using the toilet, and of those, only 50% do so correctly.
[src:escalator/airport] In airport settings, just one in five individuals maintain clean hands—defined as washing with soap for at least 15 seconds in the preceding hour.
[src:escalator/airport] Given the frequent touching of shared surfaces in airports, such as trays, railings, and touch panels, this poses a significant risk for disease transmission.
[src:escalator/airport] A study from the University of Cyprus and MIT used models and simulations to demonstrate that increasing hand cleanliness from 20% to 30% in all airports could reduce the potential global impact of a disease by 24%.
[src:escalator/airport] If cleanliness levels reached 60%, this impact could decrease by 69%.
[src:escalator/airport] Focusing on just the top 10 most influential airports for disease spread, enhancing hand hygiene practices could still significantly reduce disease transmission rates from 45% to 37%.
[src:escalator/airport] The findings underscore the importance of promoting hand-washing in airports as a key measure in preventing the global spread of diseases.
[src:escalator/airport] An airbase, sometimes referred to as an *air station* or *airfield*, provides basing and support of military aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airbases, known as *military airports*, provide facilities similar to their civilian counterparts.
[src:escalator/airport] For example, RAF Brize Norton in the UK has a terminal that caters to passengers for the Royal Air Force's scheduled flights to the Falkland Islands.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airbases are co-located with civilian airports, sharing the same ATC facilities, runways, taxiways and emergency services, but with separate terminals, parking areas and hangars.
[src:escalator/airport] Bardufoss Airport, Bardufoss Air Station in Norway and Pune Airport in India are examples of this.
[src:escalator/airport] An aircraft carrier is a warship that functions as a mobile airbase.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft carriers allow a naval force to project air power without having to depend on local bases for land-based aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] After their development in World War I, aircraft carriers replaced the battleship as the centrepiece of a modern fleet during World War II.
[src:escalator/airport] Most airports in the United States are designated "private-use airports" meaning that, whether publicly- or privately owned, the airport is not open or available for use by the public (although use of the airport may be made available by invitation of the owner or manager).
[src:escalator/airport] Most airport names include the location.
[src:escalator/airport] Many airport names honour a public figure, commonly a politician (e.g., Charles de Gaulle Airport, George Bush Intercontinental Airport, Lennart Meri Airport, O.R.
[src:escalator/airport] Tambo International Airport, Soekarno–Hatta International Airport), a monarch (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport, King Shaka International Airport), a cultural leader (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Liverpool John Lennon Airport, Leonardo da Vinci-Fiumicino Airport, Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport) or a prominent figure in aviation history of the region (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Sydney Kingsford Smith Airport), sometimes even famous writers (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Allama Iqbal International Airport) and explorers (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Some airport names include the word "International" to indicate their ability to handle international air traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] This includes some airports that do not have scheduled international airline services (e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] The earliest aircraft takeoff and landing sites were grassy fields.
[src:escalator/airport] The plane could approach at any angle that provided a favorable wind direction.
[src:escalator/airport] A slight improvement was the dirt-only field, which eliminated the drag from grass.
[src:escalator/airport] However, these functioned well only in dry conditions.
[src:escalator/airport] Later, concrete surfaces would allow landings regardless of meteorological conditions.
[src:escalator/airport] The title of world's oldest airport is disputed.
[src:escalator/airport] Toussus-le-Noble airport near Paris was established in 1907 and has been operating since.
[src:escalator/airport] College Park Airport in Maryland, US, established in 1909 by Wilbur Wright serves only general aviation traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] Beijing Nanyuan Airport in China, which was built to accommodate planes in 1904, and airships in 1907, opened in 1910.
[src:escalator/airport] It was in operation until September 2019.
[src:escalator/airport] Pearson Field Airport in Vancouver, Washington, United States, was built to accommodate planes in 1905 and airships in 1911, and is still in use as of April 2026.
[src:escalator/airport] Hamburg Airport opened in January 1911, making it the oldest commercial airport in the world which is still in operation.
[src:escalator/airport] Bremen Airport opened in 1913 and remains in use, although it served as an American military field between 1945 and 1949.
[src:escalator/airport] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol opened on September 16, 1916, as a military airfield, but has accepted civil aircraft only since December 17, 1920, allowing Sydney Airport—which started operations in January 1920—to claim to be one of the world's oldest continuously operating commercial airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Minneapolis-Saint Paul International Airport in the US opened in 1920 and has been in continuous commercial service since.
[src:escalator/airport] It serves about 35,000,000 passengers each year and continues to expand, recently opening a new 11,000-foot (3,355 m) runway.
[src:escalator/airport] Of the airports constructed during this early period in aviation, it is one of the largest and busiest that is still currently operating.
[src:escalator/airport] Don Mueang International Airport near Bangkok, Thailand, opened 1914, is also a contender, as well as the Rome Ciampino Airport, which opened in 1916.
[src:escalator/airport] Increased aircraft traffic during World War I led to the construction of landing fields.
[src:escalator/airport] Aircraft had to approach these from certain directions and this led to the development of aids for directing the approach and landing slope.
[src:escalator/airport] Following the war, some of these military airfields added civil facilities for handling passenger traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] One of the earliest such fields was Paris – Le Bourget Airport at Le Bourget, near Paris.
[src:escalator/airport] The first airport to operate scheduled international commercial services was Hounslow Heath Aerodrome in August 1919, but it was closed and supplanted by Croydon Airport in March 1920.
[src:escalator/airport] In 1922, the first permanent airport and commercial terminal solely for commercial aviation was opened at Flughafen Devau near what was then Königsberg, East Prussia.
[src:escalator/airport] The airports of this era used a paved "apron", which permitted night flying as well as landing heavier aircraft.
[src:escalator/airport] The first lighting used on an airport was during the latter part of the 1920s; in the 1930s approach lighting came into use.
[src:escalator/airport] These indicated the proper direction and angle of descent.
[src:escalator/airport] The colours and flash intervals of these lights became standardized under the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO).
[src:escalator/airport] In the 1940s, the slope-line approach system was introduced.
[src:escalator/airport] This consisted of two rows of lights that formed a funnel indicating an aircraft's position on the glideslope.
[src:escalator/airport] Additional lights indicated incorrect altitude and direction.
[src:escalator/airport] After World War II, airport design became more sophisticated.
[src:escalator/airport] Passenger buildings were being grouped together in an island, with runways arranged in groups about the terminal.
[src:escalator/airport] This arrangement permitted expansion of the facilities.
[src:escalator/airport] But it also meant that passengers had to travel further to reach their plane.
[src:escalator/airport] An improvement in the landing field was the introduction of grooves in the concrete surface.
[src:escalator/airport] These run perpendicular to the direction of the landing aircraft and serve to draw off excess rainwater that could build up in front of the plane's wheels.
[src:escalator/airport] Airport construction boomed during the 1960s with the increase in jet aircraft traffic.
[src:escalator/airport] Runways were extended out to 3,000 m (9,800 ft).
[src:escalator/airport] The fields were constructed out of reinforced concrete using a slip-form machine that produces a continuous slab with no disruptions along the length.
[src:escalator/airport] The early 1960s also saw the introduction of jet bridge systems to modern airport terminals, an innovation which eliminated outdoor passenger boarding.
[src:escalator/airport] These systems became commonplace in the United States by the 1970s.
[src:escalator/airport] The malicious use of UAVs has led to the deployment of counter unmanned air system (C-UAS) technologies such as the Aaronia AARTOS which have been installed on major international airports.
[src:escalator/airport] Airports have played major roles in films and television programs due to their very nature as a transport and international hub, and sometimes because of distinctive architectural features of particular airports.
[src:escalator/airport] One such example of this is *The Terminal*, a film about a man who becomes permanently grounded in an airport terminal and must survive only on the food and shelter provided by the airport.
[src:escalator/airport] They have also played important parts in television series like *Lost*, *The Amazing Race*, *America's Next Top Model (season 10)*, *90 Day Fiancé*, *Air Crash Investigation* which have significant parts of their story set within airports.
[src:escalator/airport] In other programmes and films, airports are merely indicative of journeys, e.g.
[src:escalator/airport] Several computer simulation games put the player in charge of an airport.
[src:escalator/airport] These include the Airport Tycoon series, SimAirport and Airport CEO.
[src:escalator/airport] Each civil aviation authority provides a source of information about airports in their country.
[src:escalator/airport] This will contain information on airport elevation, airport lighting, runway information, communications facilities and frequencies, hours of operation, nearby NAVAIDs and contact information where prior arrangement for landing is necessary.
[src:escalator/airport] , a government owned corporation charged with managing Australian ATC.
[src:escalator/airport] services for multiple European countries.
[src:escalator/airport] (Federal Office for Civil Aviation of Germany).
[src:escalator/airport] edited by Delville and published by Breitling.
[src:escalator/airport] Pooley's also contains information on some continental European airports that are close to Great Britain.
[src:escalator/airport] also publishes an online AIP for the UK.
[src:escalator/airport] (A/FD) (now officially termed the Chart Supplement) published in seven volumes.
[src:escalator/airport] also includes extensive airport data but has been unavailable to the public at large since 2006.
[src:escalator/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:escalator/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:escalator/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:escalator/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:escalator/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:escalator/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:escalator/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:escalator/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:escalator/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:escalator/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:escalator/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:escalator/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:escalator/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:escalator/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:escalator/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:escalator/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:escalator/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:escalator/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:escalator/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:escalator/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:escalator/escalator] An **escalator** is a moving staircase which carries people between floors of a building or structure.
[src:escalator/escalator] It consists of a motor-driven chain of individually linked steps on a track which cycle on a pair of tracks which keep the step tread horizontal.
[src:escalator/escalator] Escalators are often used around the world in places where lifts would be impractical, or they can be used in conjunction with them.
[src:escalator/escalator] Principal areas of usage include department stores, shopping malls, airports, transit systems (railway/railroad stations), convention centers, hotels, arenas, stadiums and public buildings.
[src:escalator/escalator] Escalators have the capacity to move large numbers of people.
[src:escalator/escalator] They have no waiting interval (Except during mass foot traffic).
[src:escalator/escalator] They can be used to guide people toward main exits or special exhibits and may be weatherproofed for outdoor use.
[src:escalator/escalator] A non-functional escalator can function as a normal staircase, whereas many other methods of transport become useless when they break down or lose power.
[src:escalator/escalator] While similarly designed, escalators are distinct from travelators, also known as moving walkways.
[src:escalator/escalator] The latter transports people horizontally, along the same floor, not between floors like an escalator.
[src:escalator/escalator] Nathan Ames, a patent attorney from Saugus, Massachusetts, is credited with patenting the first "escalator" in 1859, even though no working model of his design was ever built.
[src:escalator/escalator] His invention, the "revolving stairs", is largely speculative and the patent specifications indicate that he had no preference for materials or potential use (he noted that steps could be upholstered or made of wood, and suggested that the units might benefit the infirm within a household use).
[src:escalator/escalator] The suggested motive power was either manual or hydraulic.
[src:escalator/escalator] In 1889, Leamon Souder successfully patented the "stairway", an analogous device that featured a "series of steps and links jointed to each other".
[src:escalator/escalator] This was the first of at least four escalator-style patents issued to Souder, including two for spiral designs.
[src:escalator/escalator] Reno patented the "Endless Conveyor or Elevator." A few months after Reno's patent was approved, George A.
[src:escalator/escalator] Wheeler patented his ideas for a more recognizable moving staircase, though it was never built.
[src:escalator/escalator] Wheeler's patents were bought by Charles Seeberger; some features of Wheeler's designs were incorporated in Seeberger's prototype that was built by the Otis Elevator Company in 1899.
[src:escalator/escalator] Reno produced the first working escalator (called the "inclined elevator") and installed it alongside the Old Iron Pier at Coney Island, New York City, in 1896.
[src:escalator/escalator] This particular device was little more than an inclined belt with cast-iron slats or cleats on the surface for traction, and traveled along a 25 degree incline.
[src:escalator/escalator] A few months later, the same prototype was used for a month-long trial period on the Manhattan side of the Brooklyn Bridge.
[src:escalator/escalator] Reno eventually joined forces with Otis and retired once he had sold his patents.
[src:escalator/escalator] Some wooden Reno-type escalators were still being used at Downtown Crossing (MBTA station) until construction for the Big Dig (c.
[src:escalator/escalator] The Smithsonian Institution considered re-assembling one of these historic units from 1914 in their collection of Americana, but "logistics and reassembly costs won out over nostalgia", and the project was discarded.
[src:escalator/escalator] Around May 1895, Seeberger began drawings on a form of escalator similar to those patented by Wheeler in 1892.
[src:escalator/escalator] This device consisted of flat, moving stairs, not unlike the escalators of today, except for one important detail: the step surface was smooth, with no comb effect to safely guide the rider's feet off at the ends.
[src:escalator/escalator] Instead, the passenger had to step off sideways.
[src:escalator/escalator] To facilitate this, at the top or bottom of the escalator the steps continued moving horizontally beyond the end of the handrail (like a miniature moving sidewalk) until they disappeared under a triangular "divider" which guided the passenger to either side.
[src:escalator/escalator] Seeberger teamed with Otis in 1899, and together they produced the first commercial escalator.
[src:escalator/escalator] It won first prize at the 1900 Paris *Exposition Universelle*.
[src:escalator/escalator] Also on display at the *Exposition* were Reno's inclined elevator, a similar model by James M.
[src:escalator/escalator] Dodge and the Link Belt Machinery Co., and two different devices by the French manufacturers Hallé and Piat.
[src:escalator/escalator] Piat installed its "stepless" escalator in Harrods Knightsbridge store, which was unveiled on November 16, 1898, though the company relinquished its patent rights to the department store.
[src:escalator/escalator] Hocquardt received European patent rights for the *Fahrtreppe* in 1906.
[src:escalator/escalator] After the *Exposition*, Hallé continued to sell its escalator device in Europe, but was eventually eclipsed in sales by other major manufacturers.
[src:escalator/escalator] The Toledo-based Haughton Elevator company referred to their product as simply Moving Stairs.
[src:escalator/escalator] The Otis trademark is no longer in effect.
[src:escalator/escalator] Kone and Schindler introduced their first escalator models several decades after the Otis Elevator Co., but grew to dominate the field over time.
[src:escalator/escalator] Today, Mitsubishi and ThyssenKrupp are Otis's primary rivals.
[src:escalator/escalator] Kone expanded internationally by acquisition in the 1970s, buying out Swedish elevator manufacturer Asea-Graham, and purchasing other minor French, German and Austrian elevator makers before assuming control of Westinghouse's European elevator business.
[src:escalator/escalator] As the last of the "big four" manufacturers to emerge onto the global market, Kone first acquired the Montgomery Elevator company, then took control of Germany's Orenstein & Koppel *Rolltreppen*.
[src:escalator/escalator] In the twenty-first century Schindler became the largest maker of escalators and second largest maker of elevators in the world, though their first escalator installation did not occur until 1936.
[src:escalator/escalator] In 1979, the company entered the United States market by purchasing the Haughton Elevator company.
[src:escalator/escalator] A decade later, Schindler assumed control of the North American escalator/elevator operations of Westinghouse, forming Schindler's American division.
[src:escalator/escalator] Authors and historians have offered multiple interpretations of the source of the word "escalator", and some degree of misinformation then proliferated.
[src:escalator/escalator] For reference, contradictory citations by seven separate individuals, including the Otis Elevator Company itself, are provided below.
[src:escalator/escalator] Seeberger trademarked the word "escalator" in 1900, to coincide with his device's debut at the *Exposition universelle*.
[src:escalator/escalator] According to his own account, in 1895, his legal counsel advised him to name his new invention, and he then set out to devise a title for it.
[src:escalator/escalator] By 1906, Seeberger noted that the public had instead come to pronounce it /ˈɛskəleɪtɔːr/ (*ESS-kə-lay-tor*).
[src:escalator/escalator] "Escalator" was not a combination of other French or Greek words, and was never a derivative of "elevator" in the original sense, which means "one who raises up, a deliverer" in Latin.
[src:escalator/escalator] The alleged intended capitalization of "escalator" is likewise a topic of debate.
[src:escalator/escalator] In 1950, the landmark case *Haughton Elevator Co. v.
[src:escalator/escalator] Seeberger* precipitated the end of Otis's exclusive reign over the word "escalator", and simultaneously created a cautionary study for companies and individuals interested in trademark retention.
[src:escalator/escalator] Design factors include innovative technology, physical requirements, location, traffic patterns, safety considerations, and aesthetics.
[src:escalator/escalator] Physical factors such as the distance to be spanned determine the length and pitch of the escalator, while factors such as the infrastructure's ability to provide support and power must be considered.
[src:escalator/escalator] How upward and downward traffic is separated and load/unload areas are other important considerations.
[src:escalator/escalator] Temporal traffic patterns must be anticipated.
[src:escalator/escalator] Some escalators need only to move people from one floor to another, but others may have specific requirements, such as funneling visitors towards exits or exhibits.
[src:escalator/escalator] The visibility and accessibility of the escalator to traffic is relevant.
[src:escalator/escalator] Designers need to account for the projected traffic volumes.
[src:escalator/escalator] For example, a single-width escalator traveling at about 0.5 metres per second (1+1⁄2 ft/s) can move about 2000 people per hour, assuming that passengers ride single file.
[src:escalator/escalator] The carrying capacity of an escalator system is typically matched to the expected peak traffic demand.
[src:escalator/escalator] For example, escalators at transit stations must be designed to cater for the peak traffic flow discharged from a train, without excessive bunching at the escalator entrance.
[src:escalator/escalator] In this regard, escalators help manage the flow of people.
[src:escalator/escalator] For example, at many airports an unpaired escalator delivers passengers to an exit, with no means for anyone entering at the exit to access the concourse.
[src:escalator/escalator] Escalators are often built next to or around staircases that allow alternative travel between the same two floors.
[src:escalator/escalator] Elevators are necessary for disability access to floors serviced by escalators.
[src:escalator/escalator] Escalators typically rise at an angle of 30 or 35 degrees from the ground.
[src:escalator/escalator] They move at 0.3–0.9 metres per second (1–3 ft/s), like moving walkways, and may traverse vertical distances in excess of 18 metres (60 ft).
[src:escalator/escalator] Most modern escalators have single-piece aluminum or stainless steel steps that move on a system of tracks in a continuous loop.
[src:escalator/escalator] Most countries require escalators to have moving handrails that keep pace with the movement of the steps as a safety measure.
[src:escalator/escalator] This helps riders steady themselves, especially when stepping onto the moving stairs.
[src:escalator/escalator] Occasionally a handrail moves at a slightly different speed from the steps, causing it to "creep" slowly forward or backward relative to the steps; it is only slippage and normal wear that causes such losses of synchronicity, and is not by design.
[src:escalator/escalator] An updated drive wheel system was patented by John P.
[src:escalator/escalator] Evans in 1995, which some escalators use today.
[src:escalator/escalator] These are often used in conjunction with the escalator, but reduce the risk of creep.
[src:escalator/escalator] The direction of escalator movement (up or down) can be permanently set, controlled manually depending on the predominant flow of the crowd, or controlled automatically.
[src:escalator/escalator] In some setups, the direction is controlled by whoever arrives first.
[src:escalator/escalator] Landing platforms are the two platforms (at the two ends) that house the curved sections of the tracks, as well as the gears and motors that drive the stairs.
[src:escalator/escalator] The top platform usually contains the motor assembly and the main drive gear, while the bottom holds the return gear.
[src:escalator/escalator] These sections also anchor the ends of the escalator truss.
[src:escalator/escalator] Each platform also has a floor and a comb bearer.
[src:escalator/escalator] The comb plates, which bolt to the comb bearer (usually 4 or 5 depending on the width of the machine), help to minimize the gap between the stairs and landing, preventing objects or persons from becoming caught in it.
[src:escalator/escalator] The comb bearer, depending on the brand of the escalator, will push back and/or up and activate limit switches in the event of an impact if something jams through the combs (typically stones, screws & popcorn) as it could be someone's shoe/item loose clothing.
[src:escalator/escalator] The truss is the hollow metal structure that bridges the lower and upper landings, composed of two side sections joined with cross braces across the bottom and just below the top.
[src:escalator/escalator] The ends of the truss are attached to the top and bottom landing platforms via steel or concrete supports.
[src:escalator/escalator] It carries all the straight track sections connecting the upper and lower sections.
[src:escalator/escalator] The balustrade is composed of handrails, balustrade panels, and skirt panels.
[src:escalator/escalator] The handrail provides a handhold for passengers while they are riding the escalator.
[src:escalator/escalator] The handrail is pulled along its own track by a chain that is connected to the main drive gear by a series of pulleys, keeping it at the same speed as the steps.
[src:escalator/escalator] Four distinct sections make up the rail: at its center is a "slider", also known as a "glider ply", which is a layer of a cotton or synthetic textile that allows the rail to move smoothly along its track.
[src:escalator/escalator] The "tension member" lies on the slider and consists of either steel cable or flat steel tape, providing the handrail with tensile strength and flexibility.
[src:escalator/escalator] The inner components, on top of the tension member, are made of chemically treated rubber designed to prevent the layers from separating.
[src:escalator/escalator] Finally, the outer layer—the part that passengers see—is the cover, typically a blend of synthetic polymers and rubber.
